<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Sihanouk Meets Hun Sen on Political Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk
met here Saturday with Second Prime Minister and Vice-President of
the Cambodian People's Party Hun Sen to discuss political issues.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Hun Sen advised media representatives that he
had reported on the situation and conditions in the country to the
king. He said they also discussed the forthcoming elections and
the progress that had been made so far.
</P>
<P>
"I have reported to his majesty the King that I and the royal
Cambodian government will try our best to make the upcoming
elections free, fair and credible, and without violence," Hun Sen
said.
</P>
<P>
The king expressed his wish to stay in Cambodia until the end
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the highest priority for Cambodia now is to
mobilize efforts for organizing the elections and for stabilizing
the country, and not about setting up an international tribunal to
try Khmer Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his grave concerns about the motives of those
countries that are urging trials for Khmer Rouge leaders now.
</P>
<P>
"We should make those considerations after the elections and
they should be decided by the National Assembly," He said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about when he would meet with Prince Ranariddh, Hun Sen
said he had once planned to meet the prince, but now he has
reasons not to meet him: one reason is that Ranariddh is still
calling himself the first prime minister, and the other reason is
connected to his relations with the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
"Our first prime minister is Ung Hout not Ranariddh," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen and his entourage arrived here Friday. He made his
first public appearance, since the death of his mother on March
10, on April 29 at a peace rally.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen and his 14-member delegation are scheduled to visit
Thailand on May 6. He and his Thai counterpart, Chuan Leekpai,
are expected to oversee the signing of agreements on drug
suppression and an extradition treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
