<HEADLINE> U.S. Vice President Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
left Saudi Red Sea coast city of Jeddah Saturday afternoon for
Palestinian self-ruled area on his mideast tour.
</P>
<P>
Before winding up his visit to Saudi Arabia, Gore told Saudi
Crown Prince Abdallah Bin Abdel Aziz Saturday in Jeddah that the
U.S. was exerting its efforts to narrow the gap between the
Palestinians and the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Vice president explained the U.S. position when he
had closed talks with Abdallah Bin Abdel Aziz, official Saudi
Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the talks focused on the U.S. efforts to revive
the deadlocked peace process, including the planned London meeting
on May 4 between U.S. Secretary of State Madeliene Albright with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Gore held his first round of talks with Abdallah on the same
topic Friday evening and he also briefed Saudi King Fahd Bin
Abdel Aziz on the outcome of talks the U.S. peace envoy to the
region Dennis Ross held with Israeli and Palestinian officials
ahead of the planned meeting in London.
</P>
<P>
The talks also covered bilateral relations and issues of
security and stability of the Gulf region as well as Iraq's
compliance with the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Abdallah exchanged views concerning ways to promote
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Gore arrived in Saudi Arabia Friday on the second leg of his
Middle East tour which already took him to Israel and will
continue to take him to the Palestinian self-ruled territories
and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
