<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Say Its Delegation Not to Come Back to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The delegation of the Afghan
Taliban militia to the current round of intra-Afghan peace talks
will not come back to Islamabad for Sunday's meeting, a senior
Taliban official here told Xinhua Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban representative to Islamabad, Abdul Hakeem Mujahid,
said he himself would represent the Taliban at the talks and would
be accompanied by some other Taliban officials based in the
Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need for the Taliban delegation to come to
Islamabad. We have already discussed all the issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Joint Steering Committee was constituted to form the Ulema
(religious scholars) Commission. It has no authority to discuss
the remaining issues on the agreed agenda," Mujahid said,
referring to the lifting of the blockade to humanitarian
assistance to central Afghanistan, the cease-fire and an exchange
of POWs.
</P>
<P>
"We have informed the United Nations and OIC (Organization of
the Islamic Conference) that the Taliban delegation will not come
to Islamabad for Sunday's meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have proposed that the Ulema Commission hold a meeting
either in Jalalabad (capital of Afghanistan's Nangarhar province)
or in Islamabad next Thursday," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the five days of talks on April 26-30, the Taliban
accepted the Northern Alliance's request to include 20 people from
each side in the Ulema Commission despite the fact that the
Northern Alliance only controls eight Afghan provinces out of the
total 26, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Taliban only agreed to allow the U.N. and
other international organizations to provide medicine to central
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid stressed that the remaining issues on the agreed agenda
should be discussed by the Ulema Commission, not by the Steering
Committee.
</P>
<P>
"I have been given the authority to talk to the delegation of
the Northern Alliance tomorrow (Sunday)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fazal Hadi Shinwari, head of the Northern Alliance
delegation to the intra-Afghan peace talks, told Xinhua that they
would go to the talks "in accordance with the promise made on
Thursday."
</P>
<P>
"We expect the Taliban will also come. If they not, we will
talk with these people (led by Adbul Hakeem Mujahid)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Shinwari also said the lifting of the blockade to humanitarian
assistance to central Afghanistan will be "a minor issue" in the
Afghan peace process and should not have been the reason for the
stalemate of the current round of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The intra-Afghan peace talks, which began last Sunday, ran into
a deadlock on Thursday due to differences between the two sides
over issues relating to the lifting of the blockade, the
cease-fire and an exchange of POWs.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was adjourned for two days to allow the Taliban
delegation to consult with their leadership on these issues. It is
scheduled to resume on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that with the absence of the Taliban delegation,
the intra-Afghan peace talks are not expected to achieve any major
breakthrough.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
