<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Ambassador: Israel-Turkey Ties to Be Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli new Ambassador to Ankara
Uri Barner said on Saturday that Israeli-Turkish relations will
continue to improve in the future.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Anatolia News Agency quoted Barner as saying in a
seminar in Istanbul that there was no need for Arab world to show
great concern over the cooperation between Israel and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the seminar "New Atlantic Initiative", he said
mutual visits between Tel Aviv and Ankara will increase in the
future, adding that the trade volume of the two countries will be
increased to 1 billion U.S. dollars from the current 650 million
dollars in the next year.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey will develop cooperation in the medical
field, said Barner, adding that medical equipment exchange is
planned between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Military cooperation between the two countries is also to
develop as Turkey and Israel are reportedly to start a new
project to jointly produce medium-range defensive missiles with a
range of about 150 kilometers, similar to the "Arrow" missiles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ankara and Tel Aviv are expected to hold high-level
military talks in Israel at the end of this month to discuss the
"threats" to the Middle East and bilateral military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Iran, Iraq and Syria are among countries which will be
reportedly discussed at talks for their alleged support for
terrorism and their efforts to increase their offensive missile
technologies, a Turkish military source was quoted by the Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Israel and the United States held joint naval
maneuvers in the Mediterranean off Israel last January, which
drew harsh reactions from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Israel is upgrading 54 Turkish F-4 warplanes under a
contract worth 632 million dollars and has also won a bid to
upgrade 48 Turkish F-5 fighters.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly expanding Turkish-Israeli military cooperation has
prompted grave concerns from Iran and Arab nations in the
region, which accused Turkey of betraying the interests of the
Muslim world by coalescing with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly explained that its military collaboration
with the Jewish state is not directed against any third party.
</P>
</TEXT>
