<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Peace-Keeping Capacity Should Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan said Saturday that Africa's capacity for
peace-keeping need to be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remark during his talks at the headquarters of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) with Secretary General
Salim Ahmed Salim.
</P>
<P>
Annan told the press after his 70 minutes talks with Salim
that the OAU and the UN need to work closely together in this
field.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that there will be a joint meeting with UN
peace-keeping experts and OAU experts to review in detail some of
the developments and steps that need to be taken.
</P>
<P>
Salim told the press that they "discussed the strengthening of
African capacity for peace-keeping, United Nations experiences
and African experiences".
</P>
<P>
He said, they agreed that the continent needed to be assisted
with necessary logistics, training and funding to deal with the
conflicts in different parts of Africa.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to collaborate in their efforts to ensure
provision of necessary inter-national humanitarian assistance to
the needy.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, both UN and OAU agreed on the need to organize
at some point, an informal brain-storming session which would
bring together representatives of the OAU together with their
counterparts from the UN department for peace-keeping operations
to discuss modalities for the enhancement of African
participation in peace-keeping operations.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, they discussed questions concerning Somalia and
Sudan and agreed to work together and find ways to strengthen the
process of Inter-governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) as
a viable option, in dealing with the problems in Somalia and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
They also considered the situation in Burundi, Rwanda,
Comoros, Central African Republic, Democratic Republic of Congo,
Western Sahara and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief is currently on an eight nation east and central
African tour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
