<HEADLINE> PNA Urges U.S. to Officially Announce its Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) once again called the United States to officially make public
its initiative on Israeli troops withdrawal from the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chief Negotiator Saeb Erekat in Ramallah made the remarks
Saturday before the U.S. Vice President Al Gore's talks with PNA
Chairman Yasser Arafat, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center
said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat called on the U.S. to officially announce its initiative
and set a time limit for Israel's response.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative calls on Israel to hand back to
Palestinians 13.1 percent more of the West Bank land in its second
troop redeployment. But Israel insists on a handback of no more
than 9 percent and opposes the U.S. initiative to be made public.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said Gore and Arafat would discuss the stalled peace
process, Palestinian-U.S. relations and the setup of a Palestinian
representative office in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will visit Cairo Sunday on his way to London to attend
the May 4 talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
who is also expected to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Banjamin
Netanyahu there.
</P>
<P>
The London talks, brokered by British Prime Minister Tony Blair
in his recent Mideast tour, aims to revive the year-long stalled
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said Arafat has ruled out the possibility of a
face-to-face meeting with Netanyahu in London.
</P>
<P>
PNA and members of the Executive Committee of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization (PLO) warned Friday that failure of the
London talks could drive the region back into violence.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian self-rule region is Gore's third leg on his Mideast
tour, which has taken him to Israel and Saudi Arabia. He will also
travel to Cairo to end his regional visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
