<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Protecting Environment of Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Vice President Masoomeh
Ebtekar Saturday called on regional countries to adopt necessary
measures to protect the environment of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Ebtekar, who is also head of the Environmental Protection
Organization (EPO), said at a seminar on the Caspian Sea
environment protection in Ramsar, Iran's northern province of
Mazandaran, that economic and industrial activities in and around
the Caspian Sea should be coupled with environmental protection
policies.
</P>
<P>
Rapid industrial and economic development can lead to the
destruction of natural resources, therefore it is necessary for
regional states to adopt sustainable development policies, she was
quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying,
</P>
<P>
She warned that the world biggest inland sea is exposed to
environmental crises, saying that fluctuations in level of the sea
waters has created many environmental problems for the region.
</P>
<P>
Ecology of the sea is threatened by various kinds of
pollutants, Iran's first female vice president said, terming the
oil pollution as being among the major pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Oil exploration and exploitation over recent decade have posed
serious threats to the environment of the sea, she said,
reiterating Iran's stance against any plan to lay oil pipelines
under the sea bed.
</P>
<P>
Ebtekar stated that Iran hopes collective efforts made by
countries and international organizations will guarantee the
success of Caspian Sea environmental protection programs.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, co-sponsored by the EPO and the United
Nations, was attended by Iran, Russia, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan
and Kazakhstan, aiming at compiling a definite regional program
on removal of industrial, oil, urban and agricultural pollutants
and preservation of biological reserves in the sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
