<HEADLINE> Some 473 Somali Refugees Repatriated From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Friday transported back home
some 473 Somali refugees from the Darwanaji refugee camp, eastern
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials working in the camp said that Friday's
repatriation brings down the total number of refugees from north
western Somalia at the Darwanaji camp to 31,617, the Ethiopian
News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR officials said the Somali refugees at the Darwanaji camp
will all be repatriated by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Somali refugees have camped at Darwanaji since 1991
following the civil war in Somalia in 1988 and the subsequent
clan conflicts between 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
Now, 225,507 Somali refugees have taken shelters at eight
camps in eastern Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, UNHCR says in its latest fact sheet that Ethiopia
is currently hosting 304,436 refugees who fled neighboring
countries, including 233,558 Somalis, 58,507 Sudanese, 8,671
Kenyans and 3,000 Djiboutians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
