<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Captures More Liberian Ex-Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- With the capture of six more former
Liberian factional fighters, the west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG said Saturday it has detained a total 88 such
persons.
</P>
<P>
Most of the fighters belonged to the defunct National
Patriotic Front of Liberia (NPFL) led by the country's
warlord-turned President Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
They were captured while fighting alongside the remnants of
Sierra Leone's ousted military junta and allied rebels in the
eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led sub-regional force, which is launching a
mopping up exercise on the remnants of the junta forces and
allied rebels in that area, has repeatedly condemned Liberia's
support to the junta.
</P>
<P>
The accusation met with strong opposition from the Liberian
government.
</P>
<P>
However, one of the six who was sent to the Sierra Leonean
capital Freetown Friday said he was among a group of former NPFL
fighters re-grouped as special task force to fight with the junta
remnants and allied rebels against ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
He said they were each given 100 U.S. Dollars, according to a
British Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG, which overthrew the junta in mid-February, has
captured most parts of Sierra Leone. Due to alleged Liberian
support, the mopping up exercise in the east has made little
progress.  
</P>
