<HEADLINE> IGC Revises Forecast For World Wheat Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Revisions have been made to initial
forecasts for wheat harvests in several major producers in
1998/99, according to an announcement by International Grains
Council (IGC) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The major wheat producers, which might reduce production, are
the EC, Kazakhstan, Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
However, these are largely offset by increases for Australia,
Canada and the United States. The net change is a decline of 1
million tons in forecast world production to 592 million tons, IGC
said.
</P>
<P>
The world wheat trade is unchanged at 98 million tons. The
increase of 2 million from the previous year reflects higher
demand for milling wheat, with durum expected to decline and trade
in feed wheat and wheat flour likely to be maintained at current
levels.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at one million tons, lower
than previously estimated at 599 million tons.
</P>
<P>
World wheat stocks at the end of the season are projected at 2
million tons. higher at 124 million tons, due mainly to a higher
estimated carryover from 1997/89, according to IGC.
</P>
<P>
On coarse grains, world production is forecast at 896 million
tons, 7 million lower than in the previous year and 16 million
below the 1996 record of 912 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
