<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Parliament Approves Government's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's parliament Saturday
approved government's harsh measures to boost the economic reform
in the oil-dependent Gulf state in context of the plunge of oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
Following a closed-door session of the parliament to discuss
the nation's financial situation, Kuwaiti Finance Minister Sheikh
Ali Salem Al-Ali said that "for the first time there is consensus
between the parliament and the government over views of a
prospective plan," according to reports of Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said "the parliament has accepted to take harsh measures
for the sake of economic reform."
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti government would present the National Assembly a clear
plan on specific economic reform proposals within a month period,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He said "we are eager to remedy the economic crisis...before
the beginning of the next fiscal year (July 1 to June)."
</P>
<P>
The nine-year low oil prices in the world market since the
start of this year has a very negative impact on Kuwaiti economy
and Kuwaiti government last week projected a 1.733 billion Kuwaiti
Dinars (5.719 billion U.S. dollars) deficit for the 1998-99 fiscal
year starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser warned last Sunday
that Kuwait could face an "economic catastrophe" if Kuwaiti
crudes remained at 10.5 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
In mid-April, Kuwaiti government approved the 1998-99 budget
which is based on an oil price of 12 U.S. dollars a barrel. It
forecasts a deficit of 5.6 billion U.S. dollars, the highest
deficit since the Gulf War in 1991 and 41 percent higher than
1997-98 budgeted deficit.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait Cabinet last Sunday asked its economic committee to
study a number of economic measures searching for new sources
of income in response to the fall of oil prices
</P>
<P>
The government wants to "diversify revenue (sources), reduce
public expenditures and improve the management of public funds
in response to fall in oil prices," Kuwaiti Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Nasser
Abdullah Al-Roudhan said last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Cabinet last Sunday discussed a memorandum by the
Ministry of Finance that deals with the impact of declining
oil prices on the treasury to finance the government's budget.
</P>
<P>
The memo "includes 27 measures that should be implemented
to cut public spending and reduce challenges facing the budget
including its deficit," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
