<HEADLINE> Arafat to Hold Talks With Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
leader Yasser Arafat is due in Cairo Sunday for talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak before attending the London meeting to
revive the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will leave for London immediately after his meeting with
Mubarak scheduled for Sunday evening, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will discuss issues possibly to be raised
during the May 4 London talks, during which U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright will meet separately with Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to sell its proposal to
keep the peace process moving, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa told reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative, which is likely to be made public in
London, calls on Israel to withdraw from a further 13.1 percent of
the West Bank over 12 weeks in its second troop redeployment, with
each step met by PNA's security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has insisted on handing back no more than 9 percent
and opposed public announcement of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said London meeting will also discuss the third stage
of Israeli redeployment in the West Bank, the guarantee for its
implementation and the timetable for the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel should have finished troop withdrawal in three stages by
this summer under the Hebron accord signed in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March 1997
after Israel decided to build a settlement in Arab East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians want as capital of their would-be state.
</P>
<P>
Wishing the London talks a success, Moussa said "the meetings
are highly significant so far as they will decisively clarify a
set of points relating not only to the Palestinian track but also
to the peace process in total."
</P>
<P>
He also warned of dangers of grave frustration and escalation of
tensions if the London talks fail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
