<HEADLINE> Iran Expresses Concern on Tajikistan Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on Saturday sent a message to the U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan, voicing Iran's concern over the growing tension and
unrest in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Kharrazi
warned of the possibility of spread of conflict in the Tajikistan
capital city of Dushanbe, saying that under such circumstances all
the agreements reached based on trust in order to pave the way for
peace and stability in Tajikistan has been disrupted.
</P>
<P>
This situation has caused much concern among the regional
countries, particularly the Islamic Republic of Iran, which
shares historical, cultural and religious commonalties with that
neighboring country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating Iran's readiness in providing all possible
assistance to bring peace to Tajikistan, Kharrazi said that as
before, Iran still believes that the only way to achieve a just
and a permanent peace in Tajikistan will be a simultaneous and
timely implementation of peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the settlement of differences should come
under negotiations and exchange of dialogs, hoping that the
Tajik two rival parties will be encouraged to continue their
negotiations and execute the previously reached accords with the
mediation of the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that the Tajik pro-government
groups and the opposition clashed in the capital during the past
few days, killing at least five people and injuring dozens of
others. 
