<HEADLINE> U.S., Saudi Arabia Pledge to Revive Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Saudi
Arabia Saturday pledged in a joint statement to cooperate in
reviving the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued at the end of a two-day visit to Saudi
Arabia by U.S. Vice President Al Gore, said that "both sides
pledged to cooperate fully in the search for just and lasting
peace in the Middle East based on Security Council resolutions 242
and 338 and the concept of land for peace."
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that the best way to achieve the peace "is by
full implementation of each side's obligations made at the Oslo
and Washington accords," The Saudi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It said Gore updated the Saudi side on America's efforts to put
the peace process back on track, including details of planned
meetings in London between Secretary of State Albright and
Palestinian and Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said "Saudi Arabia expressed its
full support for the peace efforts exerted by the United States."
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia expressed also its concern for the policies of
the government of Israel and called on Israel to fully implement
the Oslo and Washington accords and cooperate with the United
States initiative to invigorate the peace process," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time both sides "underscored the importance of
resuming negotiations on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks of the
peace process as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the two sides also discussed the situation
in the Gulf and both sides "called upon Iraq to fully implement
Security Council resolutions."
</P>
<P>
It said "both sides expressed hope that Iraq would quickly
comply with all the U.N. resolutions so that the suffering of the
Iraqi people can be alleviated."
</P>
<P>
Regarding relations with Iran, the statement said both sides
noted the recent developments in Iranian policy and looked
forward to seeing the emerging of the moderate tone translated
into actual policies."
</P>
<P>
Gore arrived in Saudi Arabia Friday at the invitation of
the Saudi Crown Prince on the second leg of his Middle East
tour which has already taken him to Israel and will continue to
take him to the Palestinian self-ruled territories and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Gore met King Fahd and held two rounds of talks with Saudi
Crown Prince Abdullah Bin Abdel Aziz in Saudi Red Sea coast city
of Jeddah. Gore said that the U.S. administration was employing
efforts to narrow the gap between the Palestinians and the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Gore left for the Palestinian self-rule territories Saturday
afternoon to continue his visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
