<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newly Discovered Galaxy The Oldest Object Ever Seen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A newly found galaxy, lying some 12.3
billion light years from the Earth, is the oldest and most distant
object ever seen, The Independent newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is calculated that light from the galaxy would have started
travelling towards the Earth when the universe was less than 800
million years-old, about one-fourteenth of its present age.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that some of the objects inside the galaxy may
be going off for the first time and making stars. Such early
starbirth is believed to hold significant information for the
evolution of the universe.
</P>
<P>
The group of astronomers, including Dr Richard McMahon from
Cambridge University, made the discovery with one of the two
10-meter twin Keck telescopes on Mount Mauna Kea, Hawaii, the
world's most powerful optical observatories.
</P>
<P>
The new galaxy has displaced the previous record-holder,
another galaxy found just in March, by dating from about 60
million years earlier in cosmic history, The Independent said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Recommitment to Principles of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Sunday called for recommitment to the principles of a free
and independent press.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of World Press Free Day, May 3,
Annan said that over the past 50 years, the world has made great
advances in fostering freedom of the press, and the United Nations
has been a persistent advocate of such freedoms and has been
instrumental in laying the legal foundations for them.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said the freedom of the press ultimately
implies freedom for reporters, broadcasters and editors to work
without interference or coercion. It means the freedom to report
events or express opinions guided solely by the highest standards
of professional ethics.
</P>
<P>
Annan said modern media are primary agents of globalization in
educating people about the world; in uncovering discrimination,
abuses of human rights and other injustices; and in giving people
throughout the world a sense that their concerns have a place on
the global agenda.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said many developing countries are
conscious of the need to improve and strengthen their media
organizations. He welcomed and encouraged all efforts to foster
such working conditions in all countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that over the past decade, the United
Nations has reported the murders of 474 journalists, which reminds
the international community of the grim reality that still hangs
over universal application of the freedom of the press.
</P>
<P>
To honor the memory of those members of the press who have
fallen in their quest to bring news to the world, to tell the
truth and to expose injustice, the U.N. chief called on this
special day for recommitment to the principles of a free and
independent press that advances a culture of respect for human
rights, for good governance, and for social integration and
development among all people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
