<HEADLINE> Leaders of Nepal, Maldives Discuss SAARC Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala and visiting Maldivian President Maumoon Abdul
Gayoom on Sunday discussed issues relating to the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Nepal's Foreign
Ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Koirala reiterated Nepal's commitment to working in concert
with the other six SAARC member countries to promote cooperation
based on trust, understanding and shared benefits.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that in the process of negotiations
on transition to the South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA), the
special needs and problems of the least developed member countries
-- Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives and Nepal -- would be fully
safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that time has come for SAARC to embark on
concrete areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Gayoom, current chairman of SAARC who is on a tour of the SAARC
capitals, arrived in Nepal Sunday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He briefed Koirala on his consultations with leaders of Sri
Lanka, Bangladesh and Bhutan during his visits to these countries,
and the progress made in implementing the major decisions of the
ninth SAARC summit held in May 1997 in the Maldives, which
includes the progress in establishing SAFTA by 2001 and in
eradicating poverty from the region preferably by 2002, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
It said the two leaders also discussed issues concerning the
environment and child welfare in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Maldivian president is scheduled to visit the
Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A member of his entourage said Gayoom's current tour of SAARC
countries will not include India and Pakistan, the other two
member countries of SAARC.
</P>
<P>
The president is expected to visit the two countries some time
before the 10th SAARC summit opens in July in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
</P>
</TEXT>
