<HEADLINE> U.N. Boss Arrives in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
arrived here Sunday for a three-day official visit to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya trip is the third leg of Annan's African tour which
has already taken him to Ethiopia and Djibouti and will bring him
to Tanzania, Burundi, Rwanda, Uganda and Eritrea before returning
to New York on May 10.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. boss is expected to meet Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi and hold discussions with leaders from opposition parties and
church bodies on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that civil wars in Rwanda and Somalia would be
likely to dominate Annan's discussions with leaders of the eight
African countries.
</P>
<P>
In the past four years, hundreds of thousands of refugees from
the Rwanda and Somalia have affected nearly all the other
countries Annan visited or is going to visit during his African
tour.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who is accompanied by his wife, was met at the Jomo
Kenyatta International Airport by Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya
Godana and U.N. officials based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
In a special report, Kenya's Sunday Times newspaper said, "We
hope and trust what you (Annan) did in Iraq and that you will
also give a try in troubled African states like Somalia, Rwanda
and Burundi and help bring sanity to countries in Africa which
have been swimming in pools of blood."
</P>
<P>
Annan is scheduled to leave the country for Tanzania on
Tuesday. 
</P>
