<HEADLINE> Parade-Cum-Carnival on Elections Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 Hong Kong citizens
participated in a parade-cum-carnival on Legislative Council
elections for the Hong Kong Island geographical constituency here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A Variety of colorful programs such as children's chorus,
instrumental music and magic performance were presented to explain
to the public the details of the arrangements for the first
Legislative Council elections of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, which are scheduled for May 24.
</P>
<P>
The proper procedure for casting ballots was demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
David Lan, secretary for Home Affairs, said the electors'
active participation in the Legislative Council elections are the
most important.
</P>
<P>
After briefing the participants on the arrangements for the
elections and voting procedures, Lan said the responsibility of
the government is to ensure the elections are conducted in a fair,
open and honest manner.
</P>
<P>
The obligations of the electors are to earnestly exercise their
civic rights to elect Legislative Council members so as to
implement the principles of "Hong Kong people administering Hong
Kong" and a high degree of autonomy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lan urged all registered electors to cast their votes on
polling day.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is divided into five geographical constituencies of
Hong Kong Island, Kowloon West, Kowloon East, "New Territories"
West and "New Territories" East.
</P>
<P>
Publicity activities have also unfolded in other geographical
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council elections will produce 60 members with
20 to be returned from the geographical constituencies through
direct elections, 30 from the functional constituencies and 10
from an 800-member Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
During the May 24 elections, a total of 156 candidates will
contest 50 seats of the Legislative Council. Candidates from 10
uncontested functional constituencies have already automatically
become members of the Legislative Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
