<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Population Growth: One of Africa's Greatest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and some sub-Saharan
countries such as Kenya, South Africa and Botswana have now
reached a critical turning point in their efforts to meet the
dual challenge of rapid population growth and poor reproductive
health, said a international study released here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Population Action International (PAI), commissioned a study
which concluded that the sub-Saharan region's prospects for
economic development largely depended on the success or failure
of governments in accelerating efforts to expand family planning
services and to combat deaths in pregnancy and childbirth and
from AIDS, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The study noted that two-thirds of countries in the region had
active family planning programs, up from just a handful in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
''This dramatic change in government policy has been
accompanied by a fundamental shift in people's attitudes towards
child bearing,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
''Urbanisation, the rising cost of education and other basic
needs, and the improved chances of survival for children are all
affecting the traditional preference for large families," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The use of family planning, although still low at 18 percent
for the region as a whole, had increased dramatically in some
countries, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
However, the study established that with only 10 percent of
the world's women, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 40 percent of
all pregnancy-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
About 22,000 African women die each year from unsafe abortion,
reflecting both legal restrictions on abortion and limited access
to contraception. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
