<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Endeavor to Protect Intellectual Property Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's classrooms in primary
and secondary schools as well as tertiary institutions are the
latest battleground in the fight against pirated goods, the Trade
and Industry Bureau said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six months, staff members from the Intellectual
Property Department (IPD) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region Government have visited 85 Hong Kong schools with more than
23,000 school children aged between 15 and 17 - a prime target of
pirated goods.
</P>
<P>
The long-term education initiative is believed to be a world
first in ongoing efforts to protect intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
The government's aim is to visit all 400 secondary schools
within the next five school years and then to start all over
again, the Trade and Industry Bureau said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Primary schools will soon receive a new teaching kit which
helps younger children understand the importance of protecting
original work through role-play exercises and a video featuring
messages from pop and movie stars.
</P>
<P>
Presentations to tertiary institutions focus on the students'
special areas of interest. Budding actors, for example, are asked
to perform in a play with a script about protecting copyright.
</P>
<P>
Three new laws -- the Copyright Ordinance, Patents Ordinance
and Registered Designs Ordinance -- were introduced in June last
year to provide greater protection for intellectual property
rights holders as well as bringing in tougher penalties for
pirates.
</P>
<P>
A Prevention of Copyright Piracy Ordinance was also passed in
March this year.
</P>
<P>
A "taking it to the schools" campaign was kicked off at the
beginning of the current school year, in September 1997, as part
of Hong Kong's concerted efforts to eliminate the manufacturing,
selling and buying of pirated goods including software, movies,
music and fashion accessories.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very strong enforcement regime through our Customs
and Excise Department but relying on enforcement is not enough,"
said acting Senior Intellectual Property Examiner Belinda Sin, who
heads the IPD's Promotion and Education Section.
</P>
<P>
"We need to get the message through to the kids who use these
products that buying them is morally wrong," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
