<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Cautious Optimism for London Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 3 (Xinhua) -- As Israeli and Palestinian
leaders are leaving Sunday for the crucial London peace talks,
there is a sense of cautious optimism about a breakthrough in
breaking the prolonged peace deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is to
hold separate talks with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat in a desperate, if not the last, bid to break the
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's media adviser, said Sunday that
his cautious optimism was not based on expectation for an
agreement but rather on the realization on both sides that some
progress must be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He repeated that Israel would not accept the proposed U.S. plan
calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback from the West Bank,
but he added that progress could be seen in reaching agreements on
opening the Gaza airport and building the Karni industrial zone
for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Washington is eager to push through its pullback plan in order
to advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace process. The dispute over
the size of pullback has been one of the outstanding obstacles
stalling the progress in the talks for over a year.
</P>
<P>
The London talks were brokered by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair during his first official visit to the region late last
month. Blair, whose country holds the European Union's rotating
presidency, tried hard to inject new impetus into the moribund
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special peace envoy Dennis Ross and U.S. Vice President
Al Gore have been in the region since last week, launching
intensive efforts to narrow the huge gap between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has publicly endorsed the U.S. plan for a 13.1 percent
Israeli pullback, while Israel has remained adamant in rejecting
the plan citing that any redeployment exceeding 9 percent would
seriously endanger its security.
</P>
<P>
There have been no clear signs so far indicating Israel's
willingness to make any compromises, but Netanyahu has reportedly
hinted that he might consider an 11 percent pullback in exchange
for tighter PNA measures in cracking down on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Although no dramatic headway was made, the U.S. diplomatic
mediation has indeed brought the two sides much closer than weeks
ago. After meeting with Netanyahu Friday, Gore said the London
talks offered a great occasion for progress, urging the sides to
seize the crucial opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed with the U.S. pro-Israeli bias and its repeated
delays in publishing the redeployment plan, the PNA still hoped
Washington would keep pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Following the Arafat-Gore meeting that ended early Sunday
morning in the West Bank city Ramallah, PNA Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath said: "On pure
forecast, the hope is not that high, but the determination is."
</P>
<P>
Shaath indicated that even if no agreement on the redeployment
would be reached in London, the U.S. should at least publicize the
13.1 percent pullback plan to keep pressure on Israel. "They
(Americans) must say something to our public, to the Israeli
public," he said.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan strongly refuted the Palestinian demand, saying
Israel did not expect any ultimatum to come out from the London
talks. "I don't think there is going to be any kind of ultimatum,
or that kind of announcement. What's important here is that the
two sides sit together and try to iron out their differences," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But for the Palestinians, as well as the Americans, it seemed
that there have been too much talks, and it is high time for
action. The U.S. urgency for quick progress in the peace talks is
intensified by the fact that according to the Oslo agreements, the
one-year countdown to the end of the Oslo process has begun in the
month.
</P>
<P>
Till now, the most important final-status talks have yet
started to address the central issues in the Israeli-Palestinian
disputes, including Jerusalem, refugees and final borders.
</P>
<P>
The continued lack of progress and deepening desperation on
the Palestinian side could lead to the unilateral declaration of
independence by the Palestinian side in May, 1999, a move that
could lead to direct confrontation with Israel and renewed
tensions in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
