<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief U.N. Military Observer Arrives in S.Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 3 (Xinhua)-- The head of the U.N. military
observer mission in Sierra Leone has arrived in the capital
Freetown to help the Nigeria-led west African force with
disarmament and demobilization of combatants in the country.
</P>
<P>
Indian-born Brigadier-General S.M.C. Joshi arrived in Sierra
Leone's capital on Friday, a U.N. statement said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The other nine military liaison officers -- two Russians, two
Zimbabweans, two Kenyans, two Botswanans and one briton -- will
arrive over the weekend," said the statement reaching here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The role of the mission is to help the Nigerian-led west
African force which ejected the military junta from Freetown in
February with disarmament and demobilization of combatants by
creating a climate of confidence in the operation.
</P>
<P>
Joshi will be based in Freetown, with other members of the
team in other S.leonean cities of Bo, Kenema, Makeni, Koidu and
Lungi.
</P>
<P>
The statement said west African chiefs of staff would meet in
Ghana's capital Accra on May 4 and 5 to discuss the objectives of
their ECOMOG force following S.leone's elected President Ahmad
Tejan Kabbah's return home in March.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on the military
junta to pressure it to restore power to Kabbah, whose 1996
election ended four years of army rule. The junta took power
after disgruntled soldiers toppled Kabbah in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
Junta loyalists and their rebel allies remain active in the
areas near the border with Liberia and Guinea, despite an ECOMOG
offensive to snuff out resistance. Fighting has focused on the
diamond town of Koidu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
