<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Forms Wage Commission for Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has set up a wage
commission for industrial workers, the independent United News of
Bangladesh (UNB) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A wage and productivity commission for public sector workers
would also be set up soon, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said while
addressing a discussion.
</P>
<P>
She said steps would be taken to solve the existing problems
faced by workers in jute, textile and yarn mills in the private
sector through tripartite consultations among the government,
owners and workers.
</P>
<P>
"Our law provides equal wages for men and women for equal labor
as we are respectful to all the provisions formulated by the ILO
(International Labor Organization) for the welfare of laborers,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are loyal to the policy that 'labor is not a commodity' and
our aim is to improve the living standard of the workers," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The government was implementing five development projects to
ensure the welfare of the workers and imparting training in 21
labor welfare centers to maintain an "excellent" working
relationship between the workers and the employers, Hasina told
the meeting on Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 180 labor disputes had been resolved since her government
was formed in June 1996, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina also said the government had taken effective measures to
resolve the issue of child labor in the country. Child workers
were gradually being withdrawn from mills and factories, and the
readymade garment industries were already free of child labor, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
