<HEADLINE> Israel to Increase Expenditure on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel is due to increase
expenditure on infrastructure projects, Israel Radio reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the new infrastructure program, which
will be unveiled by Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman in the near
future, calls for adding 1 billion shekels (about 270 million
U.S. dollars) to infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, the funding will be spent for
accelerating the construction and upgrading of roads, railroads
and major ports.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the funding is to be set aside for the housing
improvements in development towns and the improvements of tourism
infrastructure of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the program is aimed at easing bureaucratic
restrictions on economic development, including removing water and
sewage management from local authorities and creating designated
companies to run these utilities.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Treasury expected that the program would lower the
unemployment rate, which had reached 8.3 percent by February,
the highest rate since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
