<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professor Urges Further Emancipation of Minds (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing University Professor Hu
Fuming, 62, never expected that the article he drafted in a
hospital bed some 20 years ago would once again emerge as a hot
national political topic.
</P>
<P>
On May 11, 1978, Professor Hu bravely published an article
entitled "Practice is the Sole Criterion for Verifying Truth" in a
 national newspaper. The article challenged leftist thinking
centered on the "two whatevers," or "resolutely upholding whatever
policy decisions made by Chairman Mao and unswervingly following
whatever instructions issued by the late leader."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese press has showered Hu with interviews in recent
weeks and he has published a dozen of articles in the country's
official leading newspapers and magazines recalling the political
event which took place 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese press has described the professor as one of the
pioneers advocating China's emancipation of minds in the late
1970s and noted that his article helped Chinese people escape the
blind worship and rigid thinking modes characteristic of the
"Cultural Revolution" period (1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
Hu has spent the period leading up to the 20th anniversary of
publication of his article in the Guangming Daily in his office in
Nanjing, east China's Jiangsu Province, fully occupied with
interviews and writing essays for a dozen-odd news and theoretical
magazines.
</P>
<P>
The professor, a diabetic with gray hair, exhibits great vigor
when recalling his accomplishments in 1978. "Furthering the
emancipation of minds has been a pleasing aspect of my work," said
Hu.
</P>
<P>
He produced the original copy of the Guangming Daily which
carried the article and noted that the essay was initially carried
in "Theoretical Trends," the internal journal of the Party School
of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
following revisions made by the school's theoretical research
office. The article was carried on the front page of the Guangming
Daily in early May 1978.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily, Liberation Army Daily and Xinhua News
Agency carried the essay over the next few days, with the work
echoing in the hearts of people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Over the following two years, Chinese people followed Deng
Xiaoping's guidelines regarding emancipation of the mind and
seeking truth from facts and succeeded in breaking through the
rigid thinking mode of the "two whatevers."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professor Urges Further Emancipation of Minds (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu recalled his preparations for writing the essay in the late
1970s by noting, "The Cultural Revolution was over and China was
at a critical stage in setting things right. I felt the crux of
matter was emancipation of the mind at a time when country was
calling for reestablishment of the guidelines for seeking truth
from facts."
</P>
<P>
"My wife was diagnosed with a tumor and was hospitalized just
as I was preparing to write the essay. It was a very hot summer,
and I drafted the framework for the essay while spending time with
my wife," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years have passed since the debates on the criterion for
verifying truth, and the convening of the Third Plenary Session of
the 11th Central Committee of the CPC has promoted the great
emancipation of minds in the country.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that the past two decades have witnessed great
achievements in China's reform, opening-up, economic construction
and social development.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping's speeches during his 1992 south China tour was
another drive for emancipation of minds and finally settled
disputhes over whether development was on a socialist or
capitalist road and laid a theoretical basis for China to shift
from the planned to a market economy, said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hu noted that the 15th National Congress of the CPC held last
year has set forth political, economic and cultural programs for
the preliminary stage of socialism. The congress made major policy
decisions on adjustments and improvements in the ownership
structure and on restructuring state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He noted that related efforts call for continuous emancipation
of minds to realize the Party's policy decisions and fulfill
China's magnificent cross-century objectives and tasks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professor Urges Further Emancipation of Minds (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu said the reform, opening and modernization drive are a
historical process which needs continuous development and just as
the emancipation of minds cannot be finished all at once.
</P>
<P>
"At each major historic junctures, The emancipation of minds
and seeking truth are necessary at each major historic juncture to
enable people to make a breakthrough in outdated concepts and
smash the shackles of the old system in order to promote reform
and opening."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that boldly developing a non-public ownership
economy on the premise of taking public ownership as the mainstay
is conducive to the development of productive forces and social
stability and consolidation of political power.
</P>
<P>
"Some people mistake the introduction of the shareholding
system in state-owned enterprises for privatization, and believe
that the growth of foreign-funded enterprises will shake the
public ownership economy," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
"Such concepts must be changed through the further emancipation
of minds," according to Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that the adjustment in China's ownership structure is
conducive to the growth of the private economy and the
introduction of overseas funds, but will do even more good for
development of the state-owned economy.
</P>
<P>
"Emancipating public ownership from its original single form
will help the country focus on the development of sectors and
enterprises which have a decisive bearing on the national economy,
and will in turn help to give full play to the leading role of the
public ownership economy," said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hu, philosopher and an economist, was born into a poor farm
family south of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
"My family received 0.2 hectare of land following the founding
of the People's Republic of China in 1949, and I was able to
have received an education thanks to the new government's
establishment of the first middle school in my hometown.
</P>
<P>
"I belong to the first generation of intellectuals fostered by
New China, and have a profound affection for New China," said Hu,
who graduated from Beijing University and then studied
philosophy at the People's University of China.
</P>
<P>
"I have the responsibility as researcher on Marxism to
contribute my efforts to the modernization of China."
</P>
<P>
Hu has written and edited numerous books, including "The Rise
of Township Enterprises in Southern Jiangsu Province" and
"Modernization of Southern Jiangsu Province".
</P>
<P>
The professor, who also serves as vice-chairman of the Jiangsu
Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), is currently organizing some 20
researchers to write the book entitled "Study of China's
Modernization."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
