<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senators in Gulf for Troops Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A seven-member U.S. senator
delegation ended a two-day visit to Kuwait Sunday and left for
Saudi Arabia on a Gulf tour to carve out financial support for the
U.S. troops deployed in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The senators, headed by Chairman of the U.S. Senate
Appropriations Committee Ted Stevens arrived here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They have visited U.S. ground troops and airmen deployed in
Kuwait and met with Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh
Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the visit, Stevens said their Gulf tour
was aimed at finding "the answer to the problem of costs" for
U.S. military deployment in the region.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that over half of the U.S. forces are deployed
overseas in places such as Bosnia, Somali, Korea and the Gulf,
thus putting "a tremendous strain on the system to keep the
rotations and keep the deployments."
</P>
<P>
"This is the main reason why we are here, to make some
suggestions for change which will help us maintain the
commitments we have made," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Stevens said in Washington that his group's
Gulf tour was going to push U.S. allies in the Middle East to
provide funds to maintain the U.S. military missions in the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currently has 37,400 troops in the Gulf, which
include 18,000 sailors and Marines, 9,000 Air Force troops, 7,800
Army soldiers and 2,600 other personnel. Half of the troops were
deployed during the U.N.-Iraq crisis over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Washington has decided to keep the military presence in the
region to monitor a test of Iraq's compliance with a
Iraq-U.N. deal on allowing U.N. inspectors in charge of
dismantling weapons of mass destruction in Iraq access to all
sites, including presidential compounds.
</P>
<P>
The deal signed between Baghdad and U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan in February has averted a U.S.-led military strike against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Stevens said that to maintain the increased U.S. military
deployment in the Gulf region, Washington needs more financial
support from its Gulf allies.
</P>
<P>
"We assume we are going to be here for a very long time and
that we need greater support," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that just like the case of Desert Storm (code name
of the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq's invasion of Kuwait), we should
have a coalition support for the forces that are here," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, it was reported that most of the Gulf countries are
reluctant to share the billion-dollar-worth bills for the U.S.
military deployment. Some of the countries are still ridden under
financial pressure caused by huge payments to the U.S.-led
military operations in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
So far, Kuwait, which was liberated by the U.S.-led allied
troops from Iraq's occupation in 1991, was known as the only Gulf
state willing to fund the U.S. military presence in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
