<HEADLINE> Israel to Appoint New Chief of General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel is to appoint the next
chief of general staff of its army to replace the incumbent Amnon
Lipkin Shahak, who will step down on July 9, Israel Radio
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two top candidates are General Matan Vilani, a former
deputy chief of general staff, and General Shaul Mofaz, who is
the incumbent deputy chief of general staff.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
has made decision on his choice and would report it to the next
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Early reports said Mofaz, 50, is Mordechai's candidate. But
defense sources noted that Mordechai has never publicly backed
Mofaz, and has expressed support for him only in a very few
forums in private.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who will meet the
two candidates before he leaves for London on Sunday, is also
reportedly leaning toward Mofaz, though Vilnai, 54, is one of his
childhood friends.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, members of the general staff have kept quiet about
who they favor to be the next chief of staff. But one general
said it was widely believed that Vilnai deserves the job.
</P>
<P>
The radio report said that any decision would require cabinet
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
