<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian-German Trade Up by 16 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian-German trade increased
by 16 percent in 1997, the Nigerian This Day newspaper quoted
German Federal Statistic Office as reporting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Citing the latest statistics compiled by the German Federal
Statistic Office, the paper said that Germany's imports from
Nigeria stood at 860 million U.S. Dollars last year, up 22.2
percent from 707 million U.S. Dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total German imports from Nigeria, crude oil accounted
for 94.6 percent with a value of 817 million U.S. Dollars in
1997, a growth of 23.5 percent over 1996's 661 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the export front, Germany sold 728 million U.S. Dollars
worth of goods to Nigeria in 1997, 11.5 percent more than the
previous year's 655 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A statistical breakdown shows that the 1997 German exports to
Nigeria include 60.4 million U.S. Dollars of chemicals, 172.5
million U.S. Dollars of machines, 147.7 million U.S. Dollars of
vehicles, 106.29 million U.S. Dollars of electro-technical
products and 90.27 million U.S. Dollars of iron and iron
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
