<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Accuse Opposition of Sabotaging Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia on
Sunday accused the rival Northern Alliance of sabotaging the
intra-Afghan peace talks, ignoring "certain concessions" made by
the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Intra-Afghan peace talks, or the first meeting of the newly
formed Afghan Joint Steering Committee, broke down here Sunday
because of sharp differences between the two sides over certain
issues.
</P>
<P>
The ostensible reason for the breakdown was the refusal by the
Northern Alliance to talk with the Taliban because of the changing
of the Taliban delegation.
</P>
<P>
The previous five-member Taliban delegation led by Abdul Wakeel
failed to return to Islamabad for the scheduled meeting with the
Northern Alliance on Sunday. The Northern Alliance raised
objections to the authority of the three-member Taliban delegation
led by Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, the Taliban representative based in
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The new Taliban delegation to the proposed meeting on Sunday
also consisted of two other Taliban officials based in the
Pakistani capital.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, the Taliban delegation accused the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance of "openly and practically"
expressing its "dislike with efforts being made for seeking a
peaceful and negotiated solution to the on-going crisis in our
war-ravaged country by refraining from participation in the
meeting."
</P>
<P>
The refusal by the Northern Alliance "thus inflicted a damaging
blow to the success of the talks, and to the hopes and
expectations of the people of Afghanistan in general," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban also accused the Northern Alliance of sending to
the meeting "a low profile nine-member delegation instead of five
members."
</P>
<P>
"The composition of the opposition delegation looked unnatural
from the very beginning as it lacked representation from other
factions such as Hekmatyar, Sayyaf, Masud and Naderi," the Taliban
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two Afghan warring factions agreed last Wednesday to form
the proposed Ulema (religious scholars) Commission with 40
representatives by equal participation of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
However, their positions are divergent on which organization
should deal with the remaining issues of the agenda, including the
lifting of the blockade of humanitarian assistance, the cease-fire
and an exchange of POWs.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban insisted that these issues be discussed by the
Ulema Commission. But the Northern Alliance held that it was up to
the Steering Committee to consider the issues.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban statement said the Northern Alliance's stance
towards the Ulema Commission was "unprincipled and unreasonable,"
and was "intending to damage the idea of the Ulema Commission."
</P>
<P>
Holding the Taliban responsible for the stalemate of the talks,
Rasool Talib, spokesman for the Northern Alliance, said the Afghan
nation has "lost another opportunity for peace because of the
negative attitude of the Taliban."
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban are still dreaming of a military solution for the
Afghan conflict. We have accepted the Taliban's first demand to
form the Ulema (religious scholars) Commission)," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban have political ambitions, and are not even ready
to remove the blockade for delivery of humanitarian assistance to
central Afghanistan," said Talib.
</P>
<P>
If the Taliban open the roads leading to central Afghanistan
for delivery of humanitarian assistance, "it will be a good
gesture for confidence building measures," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talib also accused the Taliban of violating the agreement
reached by the two sides earlier in the talks by changing their
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"We have come here with full guarantee, but they (the Taliban)
did not. We gave them two days to go back to consult their
leaders, but they did not come back," Talib said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance was "working for peace," said Talib,
adding that "We will defend the Afghan nation against any military
aggression."
</P>
<P>
"There is no military solution for the Afghan problem," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, acting chief of the U.N. Peace Mission on
Afghanistan, James Ngobi, who is also co-chairman of the meeting
of the Afghan Steering Committee, announced that there would be no
session between the two Afghan warring factions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the breakdown of the talks, Ngobi said the two
warring factions were unable to meet because of their sharp
divisions on certain issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
