<HEADLINE> Army Not to Tolerate Actions to Disrupt Elections: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos said
Sunday that the armed forces will not tolerate any actions to
disrupt the May 11 national and local elections in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Clark Special Economic Zone, the
northern Philippines, Ramos warned that the army will deal with
"all groups with evil designs, intentions and plans" to
destabilize the nation "whether during the elections or during
some other time."
</P>
<P>
"The Armed Forces of the Philippines, supported by the
Philippine National Police, the entire government and the people,
will not tolerate actions which will break the unity of the nation
and the peaceful conditions of the country," he said
</P>
<P>
Ramos was reacting to reports that the rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front will disrupt next week's presidential,
congressional and local elections if the polls will be conducted
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is limited to a single six-year term by the
constitution, called on all the people, "regardless of their
political affiliation or learning," to help establish and solidify
national unity, political stability and peace, and to ensure
honest, orderly, and peaceful elections on May 11.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever has designs, intentions or plans to create or foment
(troubles) in the country will just be hurting themselves," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the government forces, supported by the police and
with the full backing of the entire government machinery and the
civilian communities, will "be together in maintaining our unity,
our peaceful conditions."
</P>
<P>
On May 11, the nation will elect a new president, as well as a
vice president, 12 out of 24 senators, all the 256 members of the
House of Representatives, 78 provincial governors and 1,608
mayors.
</P>
<P>
But last week, the Commission on Elections warned of an
election failure in many parts of the country, particularly in
Mindanao due to potential election-related violence on polling
day.
</P>
<P>
Since the election period started in January, at least 15
people have been killed in election-related violence in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
