<HEADLINE> Zambia's Press Freedom Abuses Most Serious in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has recorded the highest
press freedom violations in southern Africa in the past
12 months, the regional media institute said.
</P>
<P>
State of the Media in Southern Africa 1997 published by the
Media Institute of Southern Africa last week said that Zambia
recorded 51 entries of abuses as compared to South Africa with
44, Swaziland with 14, Tanzania with 12, Lesotho with nine,
Botswana with eight, Namibia with seven, Zimbabwe and Malawi with
six, Mozambique with three, and Angola with one, Zambia Daily Mail
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
About Zambia, the publication said, "Zambia needs to be
singled out, not only for leading the pack in the number of
alerts it attracted, but also because of the nature of these
alerts."
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that these alerts deal with "arrests,
detentions and imprisonment of journalists; journalists in
hiding; journalists being taken for questioning by the police and
physical attack by supporters of both the ruling and the
opposition parties."
</P>
<P>
Frequent government threats to close down or ban newspapers
are some of the violations, said the publication.
</P>
<P>
On South Africa, it indicated that the country's press freedom
abuses are on the increase.
</P>
<P>
For Zimbabwe and Angola, the publication said that they
recorded low figures because of weak monitoring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
