<HEADLINE> Iran to Invest 700 Million Dollars to Boost Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran will invest 700 million
U.S. dollars during the current Iranian year (started March 21)
to boost its steel production and exports, the daily newspaper
Iran News reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an inspection to the Iran International Engineering Company
on Saturday, Iran's Minister of Mines and Metals Eshaq Jahangiri
said the investment would be used to develop steel mills in Iran
to boost the export of 1.3 million tonnes of steel products during
this Iranian year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Jahangiri announced that Iran had exported 830,000
tonnes of steel products during the past Iranian year, showing a 85
percent increase over the year before.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry planned to increase the capacity
of steel production to 12 million tonnes annually by the end of the
second five-year development plan (1995-2000).
</P>
<P>
So far, there has been no official figures about Iran's steel
production during the past Iranian year, but it was reported that
the production reached 6 million tonnes in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
