<HEADLINE> Opposition Blames Taliban for Afghan Talks Breakdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan nation has lost another
opportunity for peace as the intra-Afghan peace talks between the
two warring factions broke down here Sunday, said Rasool Talib,
spokesman for the Northern Alliance delegation.
</P>
<P>
"I am announcing with heavy hurt that the Afghan nation has
lost another opportunity for peace because of the negative
attitude of the Taliban," Talib told the waiting reporters at the
Punjab House, the venue of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban are still dreaming of a military solution for the
Afghan conflict. We have accepted the Taliban's first demand to
form the Ulema (religious scholars) Commission)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance had prepared a list for the proposed
Ulema Commission in December last year, but it was rejected by the
Taliban, Talib noted.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban have political ambitions, and are not even ready
to remove the blockade for delivery of humanitarian assistance to
central Afghanistan," said Talib.
</P>
<P>
If the Taliban open the roads leading to central Afghanistan
for delivery of humanitarian assistance, "it will be a good
gesture for confidence building measures," he added.
</P>
<P>
Talib accused the Taliban of violating the agreement reached by
the two sides earlier in the talks by changing their delegation.
</P>
<P>
"We have come here with full guarantee, but they (the Taliban)
did not. We gave them two days to go back to consult their
leaders, but they did not come back," Talib said.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance was "working for peace," said Talib,
adding that "We will defend the Afghan nation against any military
aggression."
</P>
<P>
"There is no military solution for the Afghan problem," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance spokesman appreciated the peace efforts
made by the U.N., the Organization of the Islamic Conference,
Pakistan, Iran and other countries in organizing the talks between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, acting chief of the U.N. Peace Mission on
Afghanistan, James Ngobi, announced that there would be no session
between the two Afghan warring factions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the breakdown of the Afghan peace talks, Ngobi said
the two warring factions were unable to meet because of sharp
differences over certain issues.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the Northern alliance blamed each other before
the reporters for the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance raised objections to the authority of the
three-member Taliban delegation led by Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, the
Taliban representative based in Islamabad, and refused to talk
with them.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid, however, said the delegation led by him had the full
authority and was representing "the Afghan government."
</P>
<P>
Mujahid, who was leading the three-member Taliban delegation
consisting of Taliban officials in the Pakistani capital, said
earlier before proceeding to the meeting room: "I am representing
the Afghan government with full authority."
</P>
<P>
The previous five-member Taliban delegation led by Abdul Wakeel
failed to return to Islamabad for the scheduled meeting with the
Northern Alliance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid said late Saturday afternoon that "there is no need for
the Taliban delegation to return to Islamabad. We have already
discussed all the issues."  
</P>
</TEXT>
