<HEADLINE> El Nino May Lure Sharks into HK Waters Earlier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Sharks might make an early
appearance in Hong Kong waters this summer if the El Nino
phenomenon increases the temperature of the sea, a marine expert
has warned.
</P>
<P>
Yvonne Sadovy, associate professor of the University of Hong
Kong's Ecology and Biodiversity Department, told English-language
newspaper South China Morning Post that sharks were drawn by warm
water in the summer months - from May to September. And an early
rise in water temperatures could attract sharks early in the
season.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Sunday quoted the associate professor as saying
that if the water temperature is changing differently this year
from others, it can definitely affect the appearance of the
sharks.
</P>
<P>
There had been little obvious evidence that other environmental
factors such as rainfall had affected the behavior of shark, she
said.
</P>
<P>
Seven people have been killed in shark attacks in Hong Kong
waters in the past six years. Four of the deaths occurred in 1993
and the rest, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Sadovy called for more in-depth studies of sharks off Hong Kong
 waters and make the public more aware of the patterns of
appearance of sharks especially when divers and swimmers want to
use waters outside the protected areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
