<HEADLINE> Drug Addicts Double in Iran in 4 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of drug addicts in Iran
has doubled over the past four years to around one million, the
English daily Tehran Times reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a press release from Iran's anti-drug
headquarters as saying that the sharp growth has forced the
government to consider creating more special camps for
drug-related prisoners.
</P>
<P>
It gave no further details, but serious economic hardship with
high inflation, unemployment, and the country's adjacency to drug
producing areas was believed to be the main reasons behind the
involvement of the young and poor people in drug trafficking and
addicting.
</P>
<P>
Iran neighbors the "Golden Crescent" drug-producing center
located in the border areas between Afghanistan and Pakistan and
in recent years, it has become an important transit point for drug
trafficking from the areas.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been carrying out strict anti-drug campaigns since
January 1989 with the imposing of tough laws against drug
dealers.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that 191 tonnes of various narcotics had
been seized in Iran during the past Iranian year (ended March 20)
while 2,500 people lost their lives in the campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
