<HEADLINE> Jordanian Lawyer Entrusted to Sue Israeli Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A Jordanian lawyer has been entrusted
by the Arab Lawyers' Union (ALU) to file a lawsuit against Israeli
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon for his threat to kill
anti-Israel Hamas leader Khaleed Misha'al.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer, Hussein Mjalli, will soon start to prepare the case,
which includes a request to indict Sharon, two Israeli
intelligence service Mossad's members as well as the Israeli
government, semi-official Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the ALU, Majlli will ask at the International
Court of Justice at the Hague Israel to pay compensation to
Misha'al for material and other damages incurred by Sharon's
threat.
</P>
<P>
Sharon stated on March 14 on Israeli television that Israel
still intended to assassinate Misha'al despite the failure of its
former attempt by two Mossad agents on September 25, 1997 in Amman.
</P>
<P>
In a case sheet handed to the Jordanian lawyer, the ALU said
that "this open threat, which was carried by news agencies and the
media, is an act of terrorism, a flagrant violation of
international laws and an unprecedented violation of human rights
and the United Nations charter."
</P>
<P>
The sheet also insisted that Sharon's remarks are "violation
of international relations and an act against peace and
humanity."
</P>
<P>
The ALU has referred the case to a group of Arab legal experts
for endorsement before filing it at the international court.
</P>
</TEXT>
