<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Normal" Triglyceride Levels Still Risky, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 2 (Xinhua) -- People with "normal" levels of
cholesterol and triglycerides may still be at risk of heart
disease, American researchers said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
So-called normal levels of triglycerides are anywhere between
100 and 200 milligrams per deciliter of blood. This is a standard
measurement used around the world.
</P>
<P>
But a team, headed by Dr. Michael Miller, a cardiologist at the
University of Maryland, has followed 350 men and women for 18
years and found that those with triglycerides at normal levels
also have heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
"Any level above 100 appeared to increase the risk," said
Miller, who recommended that guidelines for desirable triglyceride
levels be set lower.
</P>
<P>
Miller also recommended people to do regular exercise, eat food
rich in omega-3 fatty acids, such as linseed oil and fish, which
he said can break down triglycerides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0095 </DOCNO>
