<HEADLINE> Teenage Pregnancy: A Serious Problem in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Fund for
Population Activities (UNFPA) has said teenage pregnancy is a
serious problem in some African countries.
</P>
<P>
In some African countries, teenage pregnancy rates are
extremely high and girls under 20 years of age often have
children, some of them as many as three, the Ethiopian Herald
Sunday quoted UNFPA Executive Director Nafis Sadic as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Friday at the Ethiopian
Ministry of Economic Development and Cooperation, Sadic said that
birth expectancy is also as low as 12 and 13 years of age in most
countries in the continent.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the other major problem for teenagers is that
of sexually transmitted diseases like AIDS are engulfing the
continent at an alarming speed with 50 percent of the victims
being teenagers.
</P>
<P>
Sadik stated that for teenagers reproductive health has become a
serious issue and an important problem to address.
</P>
<P>
she said the UNFPA is taking steps and devising ways to curb
the problems as it has been doing over the years.
</P>
<P>
Reproductive health including family planning and sexual
health, population and development strategies and advocacy for
population issues are the three major areas under scrutiny, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
