<HEADLINE> Iran Raps U.S. for Charges of Supporting Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran has lashed out at the Untied
States for including Iran in "the list of countries supporting
terrorism," the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted spokesman of the Iranian Foreign Ministry Mahmoud
Mohammadi as saying Saturday that Iran itself is a victim of
terrorism and it can not close eyes to such violence.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department recently announced a list of seven
countries, including Iran, condemning them for sponsoring and
supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. accusations are incredible, Mohammadi said, adding
that Iran was confused by "the U.S. duplicity in its deeds and
words" when it talks of the undergoing transformations in Iran
during the past year on one hand and on the other it condemns Iran
as a terrorist supporting nation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S. allegations showed Washington's double
standard policy, saying such a policy from the point of view of
the international community will naturally be outright refuted.
</P>
<P>
Washington have repeatedly accused Iran, Libya and several
other nations of providing hotbeds for terrorists. It has been
pursuing the containment policy against Tehran since the 1979
Islamic Revolution in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Hopes to defrost the icy Tehran-Washington relations surfaced
after the forming of the moderate Iranian government led by
President Mohammad Khatami in August last year. The two sides have
expressed their willingness to "break the wall of mistrust"
between them.
</P>
<P>
However, the vendetta between the two sides saw little
relaxation when Tehran and Washington continued to exchange
charges against each other on many political and cultural issues.
</P>
