<HEADLINE> Afghan Peace Talks Break Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The intra-Afghan peace talks
between the Taliban militia and the rival Northern Alliance broke
down Sunday as the Northern Alliance refused to talk with the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Acting Chief of the U.N. Peace Mission on Afghanistan James
Ngobi, who is also co-chairman of the Afghan Steering Committee
meeting, told the reporters that there will no session between the
two Afghan warring factions Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ngobi announced the suspension of the Afghan peace talks,
saying the two sides were unable to meet because of their sharp
divisions on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
Both the Taliban and the Northern alliance accused each other
before the reporters for the stalemate of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Alliance raised objection to the authority of the
three-member Taliban delegation led by Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, the
Taliban representative based in Islamabad, and refused to talk
with them.
</P>
<P>
Rasool Talib said the Northern Alliance came here with
sincerity for Afghan peace and expected Sunday to talk with the
previous five-member Taliban delegation which attended the peace
talks from April 26 to 30.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid, however, said that this delegation (led by him) has
the full authority and is representing "the Afghan government."
</P>
<P>
Mujahid was leading the three-member Taliban delegation
consisting of Taliban officials in this capital city, said earlier
before proceeding to the meeting room, "I am representing the
Afghan government with full authority."
</P>
<P>
The previous five-member Taliban delegation led by Abdul Wakeel
failed to return to Islamabad for the scheduled meeting with the
Northern alliance Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid said late Saturday afternoon that "there is no need for
the Taliban delegation to return to Islamabad. We have already
discussed all the issues."  
</P>
</TEXT>
