<HEADLINE> Cholera Claims 200 Lives in Western Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan medical official has
confirmed that cholera had claimed more than 200 people in
Bushenyi District in Western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's newspaper Monitor quoted David Birungi, the district
medical official, as saying Sunday that Birungi has ordered to
close Kirugu primary school and turned it into a temporary health
center in order to receive more patients for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Richard Byaruhanga, a doctor of the Rugazi Health Unit in
Bushenyi District, told the paper that the rampant epidemic has
caused great concern in the district.
</P>
<P>
Some residents of Kafuro village claimed that there are two
deaths in their village every day.
</P>
<P>
The patients are mainly the children in the affected areas,
Birungi said, adding that the main causes of the rampant disease
are poor personal hygiene and sanitation.
</P>
<P>
He added that Medicines Sans Frontier from Holland has
dispatched a team of doctors to treat patients in the district.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, in eastern Mbale District, markets
and drinking places opened again after a six-month closure,
thanks to the improvement of the health situation there.
Mbale had been one of the worst affected areas since last November.
</P>
