<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Officials from national carrier Royal
Jordanian (RJ) Sunday continued the consultation with their
Israeli counterparts on why the RJ flights to and from Europe and
North America were not allowed to fly over Israel Saturday.
</P>
<P>
No progress has been reported up to now and the Israelis have
not given reasons for their action, Jordan's official news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
RJ officials started the consultation right after the RJ
flights were barred from using Israeli airspace and diverted to
fly through Syrian airspace on Saturday, semi-official Jordan
Times Sunday quoted a senior RJ official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nader Dahabi, the RJ's president, said that "the Israelis have
closed their airspace for reasons which until now are not clear to
us," adding that "therefore, our planes were not able to fly over
Israel and were forced to use other routes."
</P>
<P>
The ban was in force until Saturday night and "we are making
contacts with them to find out the reasons behind the closure of
their airspace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Israel Radio reported earlier that the Israeli
"controllers" restricted the number of RJ flights because the
number of controllers on duty Saturday had been cut by half.
</P>
<P>
The decision to cut the staff of controllers by half was
taken by the Israeli airport authority and the Transportation
Ministry, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israel agreed to allow Jordanian civil airplanes to fly
through its airspace shortly after the October 1994 peace treaty
between the two countries. 
</P>
