<HEADLINE> Survey: Qigong Helps Prolong Lives of Cancer Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A sample survey shows that cancer
patients can prolong their lives by doing qigong and other types
of traditional Chinese physical exercises, in addition to receiving
orthodox medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that the five-year survival rate of cancer
patients in Shanghai, one of the Chinese cities that witnesses a
high incidence of cancers, has been raised from 33.6 percent in
1993 to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sample survey, covering the 3,173 members of the Shanghai
Cancer Rehabilitation Club, said about 88 percent indulge in
regular physical training of various kinds.
</P>
<P>
Over 59 percent of the members do Guo Ling Qigong -- a
breathing exercise specially designed for cancer patients -- the
survey disclosed.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 66.5 percent of them report no more of the
negative reactions associated with cancer; 39.7 percent report an
increase in their white corpuscles; and 40.8 percent
said that they are sleeping better.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that 82 percent of the members have had
their tumors removed, and 46.7 percent have received chemotherapy after
undergoing operations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
