<HEADLINE> Zambia, Vietnam Agree to Establish Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Vietnam have agreed to
establish a joint permanent commission to strengthen cooperation
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Saturday, a spokesman of the
Zambian Ministry of Foreign Affairs said the agreement was made
during talks between Zambian Foreign Affairs Minister Keli
Walubita and his Vietnamese counterpart Nguyen Manh Cam in Hanoi
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the two foreign ministers shared the
view that there is need to set a joint permanent commission of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that both ministers expressed the hope that the
existing friendship between the two countries will be
strengthered and that the commission will serve to promote mutual
cooperation in trade and economic relations, state-owned Zambia
Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the talks, Walubita requested the Vietnamese government to
consider assisting Zambia in setting up rice farms and to send
experts to teach the zambians on how best to grow rice.
</P>
<P>
Walubita noted the possibility for the Vietnamese rice to find
a larger market in southern African countries if the commodity is
channeled through Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Cam, who is also Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister, said that
Zambia would be very good market for Vietnamese products
including rice.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Vietnam is ready to export shoes, wood, fish
products and others to zambia in their efforts to enhance
cooperation between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Vietnam, Walubita also held discussions
with the Vietnamese Minister of trade and the minister of
investment and planning on the possibility of furthering
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Walubita arrived in Hanoi on 28 April for a five-day visit to
Vietnam after his tour to China. 
</P>
