<HEADLINE> U.S. Union Pacific to Upgrade Railroad Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Union Pacific Corp., the largest
railroad company in the United States, said on Saturday that it would
spend more than 1.4 billion dollars over the next five years to
expand and upgrade its railroad tracks, connections and terminals
in Texas and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
"Over the next few years, we are going to make an all-out effort to
align our railroad operations, route structure and capacity investment
with our customers' needs and plans for future growth," said Union
Pacific's chief executive, Dick Davidson, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The congestion problems, which started last summer, spilled over
into this year and caused the company to post a 62-million-dollar loss
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, delays have infuriated customers, some of whom, such
as Union Carbide Corp., have sued the railroad company.
</P>
<P>
Union Pacific said it would spend up to 63 million dollars on its
major terminals in Houston, 161 million dollars on regional terminals
in Dayton and Strang, Texas, and Lake Charles, Louisiana, 285 million
dollars on expanding line capacity, 82 million dollars on additional
tracks for storage of Gulf Coast chemical business, and 29 million
dollars on connections.
</P>
<P>
The company has targeted the remaining 830 million dollars to
upgrade its tracks, ballast and signaling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
