<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks 20th Anniversary of Ideological Debate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 3 (Xinhua) -- China's media and ideological
circles have been launching various activities lately to mark the
20th anniversary of the publishing of the article "Practice Is
Sole Criterion of Testing Truth". The article had sparked a
nationwide debate and later helped lay the ideological foundation
for the country's economic reform after decade-long disastrous
cultural revolution.
</P>
<P>
"Criterion of truth" that were repeatedly referred to in
discussions 20 years ago once again become catch phrase in newspapers,
on television and radio. China Central Television and many local
television stations are busy shooting documentaries of the
three-year long debate. Various seminars on theory are now
underway.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration is expected to reach the climax on May 11,
the day on which the famous article was published in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Leading the activities are Chinese acdemic and ideological
circles which have run a series seminars to commemerate the
event.
</P>
<P>
But in the words of Liu Ji, vice-president of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, the commemoration of the debate is
never meant for reviewing the past, instead, it calls for the
promotion of spirit of judging truth from practice and moving ahead
with the present reform.
</P>
<P>
Gong Yuzhi, vice-president of the Party School of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), pointed out that
the significance of the debate on the criterion of truth lies in
the fact that it laid an important ideological basis for the Third
Plenary Session of the 11th CPC Central Committee, which ushered
the country onto the road of reform and opening up and initiated
the theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, or
Deng Xiaoping's Theory.
</P>
<P>
Other academics agreed that the principle of the criteria of
truth witnessed a further progress 14 years later, when Deng
Xiaoping put forth a set of criteria called "three favorables"
during his tour to south China in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In view of the timid attitudes taken towards reform and opening
up then, Deng pointed out straightforwardly, "the reason why some
people hesitate to move ahead with the reform is as a matter of
fact that they are afraid of being accused of introducing too many
elements of capitalism or taking the capitalist road.
</P>
<P>
Deng said when judging a policy right or wrong, the following
should be taken into accont: whether it is favorable to the
promotion of the growth of the productive forces of a socialist
society, favorable to the increase of the overall strength of the
socialist state and favorable to the raise of people's living
standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks 20th Anniversary of Ideological Debate  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xiao Qian, a professor with the Chinese People's University,
said the "three favorables" signified further emancipation of the
mind in China, and it made people come to realize that socialism
can make use of market mechanism, introduce foreign funds and
allow a proportion of people to get rich first.
</P>
<P>
The principle broke new ground and pushed forward China's
reform and opening-up drive in a big way, Xiao noted.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese media hold that the reform and opening-up are now
entering a critical stage, and it requires people to further
emancipate the mind and steadfastly move forward the reform.
</P>
<P>
Gong Yuzhi said the report of the 15th CPC National Congress
set out new tasks in various fields including economy, politics
and culture, and demanded an all-round emancipation of mind.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the system of public ownership can be
realized in various forms; the share-holding system is capital
organization means of modern enterprises and is fit for both
socialism and capitalism. He stressed that all these need further
study with an open mind.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wu Shuqing, former president of Beijing University,
said the reform and opening up, or the establishment of a new
socialist economic system and its operation mechanism, will
definitely break the traditional way of operation in existence for
decades, and it is sure to bring conflict with the old way of
thinking.
</P>
<P>
He noted that only when people's minds are emancipated and
testing truth from practice are sincerely pursued, can a smooth
progress of the socialist modernization be ensured.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
