<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 07:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Crime Rate Increases in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 46,713 crimes was reported
in Jordan last year, an increase of 1.94 percent from the 45,823
cases recorded in 1996, said a Public Security Department (PSD)
report issued here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The increase could be attributed to many demographic and social
changes that had affected Jordan over the past decade,
semi-official Jordan Times Sunday quoted Lieutenant Colonel
Ahmad Qudah, acting chief of the criminal information section of
the PSD, as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, high unemployment rate and juvenile
mis-conducts seemed to be most prominent factors that attributed
to the increase.
</P>
<P>
The 18-27 age bracket were responsible for the greatest number
of crimes, while 56.9 percent of persons arrested were
unemployed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qudah said that 35.14 percent of the crimes in 1997
were misdemeanor cases, 14.39 percent petty theft, 8.9 percent
acts of violence following drunkenness and 4 percent cases of
immoral acts.
</P>
<P>
Other crimes included premeditated murders, attempted murders,
forgery cases and rape cases, Qudah said.
</P>
<P>
The number of premeditated murders last year dropped by 2.78
percent over the 1996 figures, but that of attempted murders rose
by 38.58 percent, according to Qudah.
</P>
<P>
The number of forgery cases increased by 34.81 percent and
rape cases by 46.03 percent in 1997 over 1996, Qudah added.
</P>
<P>
By geographic way, the highest crime rate in 1997 was
registered in the capital city of Amman. The crimes that happened
here in 1997 accounted for 43.86 percent of the kingdom's total,
the PSD report said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the 1.94 percent increase, the PSD report said,
Jordan's crime rate is low in comparison with other Arab
countries and, most importantly, "organized crime does not exist"
in the kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
