<HEADLINE> Uganda, Kenya, Tanzania Try to Strengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Military Ties
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The armed forces of Uganda, Kenya and
Tanzania have signed a memorandum of cooperation in their efforts to
strengthen military cooperation among the three neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed Thursday in Arusha in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Caleb Akandwanaho, the Overseer of Uganda's Minister of Defense,
said the pact provides for joint training of the three armies,
cooperation during disaster times and gives access to any of the
forces to airports and airbases in the region, the New Vision newspaper
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, he said, also provides for joint use of
technical facilities where any of the armies is carrying out their
equipment maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The East African Cooperation, which groups Uganda, Kenya and
Tanzania, has been seeking to cement military as well as political
ties. 
