<HEADLINE> Serious Ambulance Shortage Facing Zimbabwe's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Harare City Council is facing a
critical shortage of ambulances, Mayor Solomon Tawengwa has said.
</P>
<P>
The fleet has been reduced to only six vehicles from a total
of 46 servicing a population of more than one million residents,
the Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The city council could not replace the depleted fleet due to
financial constraints, the paper quoted the mayor as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tawengwa said that the council is doing everything possible to
provide an additional five ambulances every year until the
situation was normalized.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted other sources within the council as saying
that the city's ambulance service was collapsing and many people
were dying in their homes because they could not be taken to
hospital in time.
</P>
<P>
The well-placed sources in the city council disclosed that the
emergency department currently needs at least 50 new vehicles to
match up with the growing Harare population. 
</P>
