<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Announces Large Food Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Affairs Minister
Alexander Downer announced on Sunday a
30-million-Australian-dollar (19.5 million U.S. dollar) aid
package to its largest neighboring nation Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the humanitarian assistance package would help feed
more than 4 million people who would not able to feed themselves
during the coming dry season because of some of the country's
worst drought conditions in decades and fallout from the country's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The main part of the package is 40,000 tons of grain to feed
malnourished and vulnerable groups in the poorer areas of eastern
Indonesia, the foreign minister said in Australia's southern port
city of Adelaide, where his family live.
</P>
<P>
The grain, special food for children and pregnant women, and
emergency medical supplies will be distributed through
international agencies, non-governmental organizations and
Australian aid project teams in the eastern islands.
</P>
<P>
Innes Willox, a spokesman for the foreign minister, told Xinhua
the package is probably the biggest single donation in the history
of Australia's overseas humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
He said the 40,000 tons of grain, mainly wheat, will be
channeled to Indonesia through the United Nations' World Food
Program, to which the United States and Japan also contributed,
Willox said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the special package was in addition to Australia's
1 billion U.S. dollars contribution to helping Indonesia as part
of the International Monetary Fund loan program.
</P>
<P>
It is also on top of 585 million U.S. dollars in Australian
government's trade insurance cover and nearly 58.5 million U.S.
dollars in an annual aid program to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Downer said 40 million Indonesians, about 20 percent of the
country's population, were living in poverty and it would be
irresponsible for the Australian government to ignore their
plight.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia was one of a number of countries sending
Indonesia relief packages, including the United States and Japan
and countries of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
In terms of its national interest, Australia regards Indonesia
as its third most important nation in the world after the United
States and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
