<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Urged to Postpone Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's General Agriculture and
Plantation Workers' Union (GAPWUZ) has called on the government
to delay the resettlement process pending enactment of the
legislation regarding the payment of terminal benefits to workers
on designated farms.
</P>
<P>
GAPWUZ Secretary-General Philip Munyanyi said in an interview
earlier that after last November's designation of nearly 1,500 farms
by the government for resettlement purposes, much attention had been
placed on the acquisition of the land without carefully examining
how the workers would receive their benefits, Zimbabwe's Sunday
Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was not clear who should pay the workers as
farmers were contending that whoever was taking over the farms,
should pay the benefits as they would be made redundant and
unproductive while on the other hand, the government had not made
a commitment to pay the workers.
</P>
<P>
According to the law of Zimbabwe, Munyanyi said, a person who
inherits a business entity must also inherit such things as debts
and other costs. " The government, through the Ministry of Lands
and Agriculture, is inheriting the farms but it is not clear who
should pay the workers,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
The union estimated that about one million people, including
workers and their dependants, are going to be affected by the
loss of the farm jobs.
</P>
<P>
Munyanyi said the state has an obligation to help workers in
the agricultural sector as they have contributed immensely to the
national economic development. ''Our economy is agro-based and
it is mainly through the hard work of farm workers that we are
earning foreign currency,'' he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
