<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-saving Wheat Developed in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- A new species of wheat specially
tailored for the dry Australian climate has been developed in the
country, experts said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Richard Richards, an expert with Australia's Commonwealth
Scientific and Industrial Research Organization (CSIRO), said:
"The new wheat grows leaves earlier in its life than other
Australian wheats -- it creates its own 'sunshade' to prevent the
soil around it from drying out."
</P>
<P>
"Saving soil moisture early in the season means there is more
water for the wheat plant to fill its grains, giving a bigger
harvest," said Richards at the CSIRO, a leading research center in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The wheat was tailored by Richards and has been developed by
Dreg Rebetzke, also of CSIRO Plant Industry with support from
growers through the Grains Research and Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"We have discovered genes that increase early leaf growth by
150-190 percent that will make our current wheats faster-growing
and higher-yielding," the expert said.
</P>
<P>
Genetic material from as far afield as China, India and Canada
was drawn and incorporated into traditional Australian wheats.
</P>
<P>
"The overall result is a bigger crop by the time flowering
comes around, yet soil moisture reserves are preserved for later
use by the grain, giving potential for significant yield gains,"
the expert said.
</P>
<P>
Wheat breeders around Australia are collaborating with the
CSIRO team and are now testing the new wheats in a series of field
trials, confident that they will deliver promising new varieties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 06:27 </DATE_TIME>
