<HEADLINE> Afghan Peace Talks Remain in Stalemate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The intra-Afghan peace talks
between the Taliban militia and the rival Northern Alliance remain
in stalemate here Sunday morning as the two sides have not agreed
as to what issues should be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the Taliban and the Northern Alliance have
entered the meeting room. Officials from the U.N. are now
mediating between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
As agreed on Thursday, the two Afghan warring factions are to
resume their peace talks Sunday after a two-day recess.
</P>
<P>
Before entering the meeting room, Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, the
Taliban representative in Islamabad, told the reporters: "I am
representing the Afghan government with full authority."
</P>
<P>
Mujahid is leading a three-member delegation from the Taliban
side to the peace talks Sunday. The previous five-member Taliban
delegation which attended the five-day peace talks here from April
26 to 30 has not returned to Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
It is not a "violation" of the agreed agenda, said Mujahid,
adding that "it is the violation by the opposition side because
they don't have full representation in the meeting (Sunday)."
</P>
<P>
"We have already agreed on the formation of the Ulema
(religious scholars) Commission, so now only the issue of date and
venue of the Ulema Commission meeting is to be discussed," said
the Taliban representative.
</P>
<P>
Mujahid said on Saturday that "there is no need for the Taliban
delegation to return to Islamabad. We have already discussed all
the issues."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Rasool Talib, a senior representative from the rival
Northern Alliance delegation said Sunday before proceeding to the
meeting room: "We will discuss the issues relating to lifting of
blockade and ceasefire."
</P>
<P>
Since the two sides have different opinions on the agenda. It
is most likely that the peace talks will end soon without any
positive results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
