<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Post-Cultural Revolution Ideological Debate (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the closing ceremony of the conference, Deng Xiaoping called
on the whole country to "emancipate the mind, seek truth from
facts, be united as one and look to the future", and spoke highly
of the significance of the debate on the criterion of truth.
</P>
<P>
"This debate is an issue concerning the ideological line, as
well as a political issue that has a bearing on the future and
destiny of both our Party and country," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Third Plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee, which was
held shortly after the conference, formally commended the debate
on the criterion of truth, and pointed out that the ideological line
of "seeking truth from facts and proceeding from reality in
all cases" initiated by Mao Zedong must be restored. This
announced the complete bankruptcy of the "two whatevers" theory.
</P>
<P>
Following the Third Plenum, the CPC Central Committee decided
to spread the debate on the criterion of truth to all parts of the
country. In 1979 and 1980 the debate was carried out in all 29
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions in China, helping
the broad masses of officials and ordinary people to shake off the
influence of the personality cult, emancipate their minds and
grasp the correct criterion for judging truth.
</P>
<P>
In June 1981, taking practice as the sole criterion for judging
truth, the 11th CPC Central Committee adopted the "Resolution on
Certain Historical Issues Concerning the Party Since the Founding
of New China" at its Sixth Plenum, marking a satisfactory end to
the great three-year great debate on the criterion of truth in China.
</P>
<P>
Though two decades have elapsed, this great debate, which
helped make ideological preparations for the epoch-making Third
Plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee, will never be forgotten
because of its profound impact on and tremendous contribution to
Chinese history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
