<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urged to Solve Banking Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Bangladeshi garment sector
have called on the government to help solve the banking problems
for the survival of the country's top exchange earner, The
Independent daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The banking problems was the number one hurdle the sector is
facing, President of the Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and
Exporters Association (MGMEA) Mostafa Golam Quddus was quoted as
saying at a round-table on "Problems and Prospects of Garment
Industries" Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"If the non-cooperation of the banks continue the sector will
collapse," he said, adding "It is unfortunate that the
manufacturers are being held hostage by the bankers and they are
taught by the clerks what is export."
</P>
<P>
"If the government does not redress the problems, our next
generation will not feel encouraged to come for setting up
industries," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Another MGMEA leader cautioned that "if the garment sector
collapses due to lack of policy support of the government, Dhaka
city would turn into a ghost city and the total social stability
will tumble as million of people directly or indirectly make their
living from the sector.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's garment manufacturing sector earns 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign exchange annually, counting for about 70
percent of the country's total foreign exchange earnings. And it
generates the largest employment opportunity with over 1.3 million
people working now in the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
