<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Economy grows by 6.4 PCT Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's economy grew by 6.4
percent last year compared with a growth rate of 3.8 percent in
1996 when the country underwent depressed conditions, the Central
Bank said.
</P>
<P>
The higher economic growth rate of 6.4 percent in 1997 reflects
not only the recovery of economic activities from the slump
experienced in 1996, but also a significant improvement in
business confidence, mainly due to the improvement of economic
fundamentals, the bank's annual report for 1997 released Friday
said.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit also declined to 387 million U.S.
dollars last year from 683 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The significant achievement of the economy is mainly due to the
increase in earnings from exports, tourism, higher private
transfers and capital inflows last year.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, agricultural and services sectors have recorded
growth rates of 10.3 percent, 3 percent and 7.8 percent
respectively last year and their contribution to the GDP was 29
percent, 8 percent and 55 percent respectively, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation dropped to 9.6 percent last year from
15.9 percent in 1996, mainly due to the improvement of the
domestic supply situation and reduction in demand pressure as a
result of the moderation of monetary expansion.
</P>
<P>
The stock market showed some improvements during last year. The
all Share Price Index increased by 16 percent in 1997 while the
Sensitive Price Index rose by 19 percent. There were net inflows
of foreign funds of 13 million U.S. dollars through the stock
market in 1997, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Post-Cultural Revolution Ideological Debate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Twenty years ago, a debate
concerning China's future and destiny swept the country. The theme
was what is the criterion of judging truth, practice or leader's
words?
</P>
<P>
The debate helped people get rid of their blind faith in late
Mao Zedong who had mistakes in his late life and was regarded as a
major ideological breakthrough in the history of the Communist
Party in decades. It was also considered an ideological
preparation for the third Plenary Session of the 11th Chinese
Communist Party Congress in late 1978 which ushered the country
into a new eara of economic reform and opening up after 10 years
of chaos.
</P>
<P>
Shen Baoxiang, professor with the Party School of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee, has just completed his ten-year
study of the debate and published a book on it. He revealed new
details of the event in an interview with Xinhua reporters.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, two years after the Cultural Revolution, people were
looking into the cause of the disastrous event led by the late
leader Mao Zedong. But the leadership in charge of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee then reiterated that people
should firmly uphold whatever decisions Chairman Mao made, and
steadfastly follow whatever instructions he gave, which was later
on referred to as "two whatevers."
</P>
<P>
Therefore an ideological confrontation between those for "two
whatevers" and those against took place. And the debate focusing
on the criterion of truth evolved against this backdrop.
</P>
<P>
In April 1977 Deng Xiaoping who had not yet resumed leading
position, detected the innate error in the much publicized idea of
the "two whatevers" and wrote to the Party Central Committee,
pointing out that "Mao Zedoong Thought must be accurately and
thoroughly understood, initiating the emancipation of the mind
within the CPC. Later on he said "'two whatevers' does not conform
to Marxism. If we cannot change whatever Mao Zedong said and done,
we will do harm to the Mao Zedong Thought."
</P>
<P>
Subsequently, some cadres and theorists advocated that practice
is the sole criterion for testing truth, igniting a three-year
debate nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The fuse which sparked the debate was an article in the May 10,
1978 issue of a periodical for internal circulation run by the
Party School of the CPC Central Committee. The article was checked
by Hu Yaobang, who was then the deputy head of the school. It was
published the second day on Guangming Daily, a national paper for
intellectuals. The article was then re-run by Xinhua News Agency,
People's Daily, Liberation Army's Daily and major local
newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Post-Cultural Revolution Ideological Debate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the theme that practice is the sole criterion for testing
truth, as well as for testing guidelines and policies, the article
criticized the "two whatevers" in an implicit way. It instantly
won wide support among the public, while arousing the disputes
among people in the higher leadership. A major debate broke out
and soon became heated and tense.
</P>
<P>
At the crucial moment, Deng Xiaoping who just resumed the
leading position, openly voiced his support for a debate to be held
on the criterion for testing truth, at a army conference on June
2, 1978.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Some comrades talk of Mao Zedong Thought all the
time, while in fact they often forget about, give up and even oppose
the fundamental Marxist viewpoint and method that emphasizes
seeking truth from facts, proceeding from reality and combining
theory with practice, which was embraced by Mao."
</P>
<P>
He quoted from Mao's writings to attack the "two whatevers" and
expound the criterion for testing truth.
</P>
<P>
Deng's speech came as an encouragement for those approving of
the principal, but the pro-"two whatevers" faction refused to back
off and tried to stifle further debate.
</P>
<P>
In the face of great pressure, those organizing the debate
demonstrated great courage. On June 16 an article on the criterion
for truth authored by Xing Bensi, a leading theorist, was
published in the ``People's Daily'' and simultaneously carried by
Xinhua News Agency, Guangming Daily and Liberation Army's
Daily. On June 24 another, titled ``The Most Fundamental Principle
of Marxism'', was launched by the army's daily and carried by all
other major media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
