<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theoretical Articles Review Emancipation of the Mind (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The latest issue of Qiushi published an article titled "On 'Two
Whatevers' and Emancipation of the Mind."
</P>
<P>
It says that 20 years later, we once again review and
commemorate the "grand discussion of the criterion of truth"
because it still bears practical significance.
</P>
<P>
The "two whatevers" as a phrase might never be used, the
article says, but as a kind of mode of thinking, it may continue
to exist.
</P>
<P>
The article pointed out that, on the one hand, government
officials are entitled to shoulder the responsibility of
publicizing Marxism and the Mao Zedong Thought among the people,
as well as implementing the Party's lines, principles and policies.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, government officials also have the
obligation to sum up people's experiences and report genuine
information to the people's government to facilitate senior
government officials' decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
The article says that only those who can both master the cream
of Marxism and sum up experience from practice could truly be
regarded as emancipating minds and seeking truth from facts.
</P>
<P>
History has proved many times that each false political
movement always goes hand in hand with a false wave of
philosophical thought, it says.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the Party in 1921, the Party has
cultivated such styles as seeking truth from facts, maintaining
close links with the masses, as well as democracy and
selflessness, which were all been greatly damaged during the
Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) under the guise of "the two
whatevers."
</P>
<P>
Today, as we commemorate the 20th anniversary of the grand
discussion and embrace the achievements of the reform and
opening-up campaign, the great banner of emancipation of the mind
and seeking truth from facts, which was held up by the late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, have proved to be essential in the
future establishment of a socialist country with Chinese
characteristics, the article states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
