<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theoretical Articles Review Emancipation of the Mind (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The latest issues of "Outlook"
and "Qiushi" (seeking truth) magazines include articles reviewing
the emancipation of people's minds during the last 20 years of
China's reform, opening-up and modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
"The emancipation of the mind started from discussions on the
argument that practice is the only criterion of truth," the
"Outlook" article said.
</P>
<P>
Guided and advocated by Deng Xiaoping, the discussions laid an
ideological and theoretical foundation for the country to launch
its significant reform, opening-up and modernization drive after
the third plenary session of the 11th Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) in late 1978.
</P>
<P>
"In the arduous process of reform and opening-up, people's
minds were unshackled. On the basis of mind emancipation, reform
and opening-up in turn scored even bigger progress," the article
said.
</P>
<P>
In the period from the third plenum to the 13th National
Congress of the CPC, the people's commune system in rural areas
was abolished, China opened itself up to the outside world and an
economic structure took shape with public ownership at the core
along with the co-existence of varied forms of ownership and
operating mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the CPC Central Committee put forward the
theory of a socialist market economy, made it clear that China is
in the primary stage of socialism during which the fundamental
task is to develop productive forces, and formed the theory of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
The article stated that mind emancipation enabled the
establishment of a socialist market economy. After the serious
political turmoil in China in 1989 and drastic changes in the
former Soviet Union and eastern Europe, the article stated, some
people held the wrong view that China's economic difficulties and
political disturbances were a result of the reform and opening-up,
and that reform brought about polarization and market-oriented
reform was a development of capitalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theoretical Articles Review Emancipation of the Mind (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The incorrect view seriously undermined the deepening of reform
and wider opening of China to the outside world, the article
stated. Under such circumstances, Deng Xiaoping pointed out time
and again that the difference of socialism and capitalism does not
lie in overall planning and the role of the market concerning
economic affairs. Socialism should not be separated from
developing a market economy and there is also planned control in
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
The major criterion to discern socialism from capitalism is to
see whether socialist productive forces can be developed, whether
the overall national strength of socialist China can be raised,
and whether the living standard of the people can be improved.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 14th National Congress of the CPC in 1992,
CPC Central Committee General Secretary Jiang Zemin said clearly
that the goal of China's economic restructuring was to establish a
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
And the report urged all Party members to further liberate
their minds, quicken the pace of reform and opening-up, and not to
shackle their minds with abstract debate on the directions of
either socialism or capitalism.
</P>
<P>
Since the 14th National Congress of the CPC, China has carried
out a comprehensive economic restructuring. A series of key
reforms was conducted in the fields related to overall planning,
fiscal systems, taxation, finance, foreign exchange, foreign
trade, overseas investment and state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the CPC Central Committee, Jiang Zemin also
pointed out that, in addition to the traditional public ownership,
various business forms which can reflect the rules of socialist
production can be boldly utilized.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, every key breakthrough in reform over the past 20
years was guided by the emancipation of the mind, and deepened
reformed in turn provided the conditions for further mind
emancipation, the article stated.
</P>
<P>
The powerful weapon to unshackle people's minds is "seeking
truth from facts," which is the essence of the Deng Xiaoping
Theory, according to the article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology: Economic and Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are the key events in the
evolution of the European economic and monetary union (EMU):
</P>
<P>
1957 -- Signing of the Treaty of Rome for the establishment of
the European Economic Community (EEC);
</P>
<P>
1970 -- Luxembourg's Prime Minister Pierre Werner proposed how to
achieve EMU by 1980;
</P>
<P>
1971 -- The United States abandoned dollar's link to gold;
</P>
<P>
1972 -- Prototype of a European monetary system;
</P>
<P>
1979 -- Establishment of the European monetary system;
</P>
<P>
1985-1992 -- Preparation of the internal market;
</P>
<P>
1986 -- Signing of the Single European Act with the goal of a
single market in Europe by the end of 1992;
</P>
<P>
1988 -- The European Commission under Jacques Delors set up a
committee for the study of EMU;
</P>
<P>
1989 -- Delors' proposal of a three-stage transition to EMU;
</P>
<P>
November 1993 -- Entering into force the Treaty of European Union
(Maastricht Treaty) with EMU as one of the basic objectives;
</P>
<P>
May 1995 -- Proposal by the European Commission greenpaper of a
transition to single currency; euro was chosen as the name for that
single currency;
</P>
<P>
December 1996 -- Publishing of designs of euro bank notes by the
European Monetary Institute;
</P>
<P>
June 1997 -- Agreement on legal framework for the use of euro at
the European council meeting in Amsterdam; announcing of designs of
euro coins;
</P>
<P>
March 1998 -- Adoption by the European Commission of
convergence report and recommendation of 11 European Union member
states as the founding members of euro;
</P>
<P>
May 1998 -- Confirmation by the European summit at heads of state
and government level of the recommendation that 11 countries are the
original members of the euro zone; European finance ministers
pre-announced bilateral exchange rates between participating
currencies and euro;
</P>
<P>
January 1999 -- The 11 EU countries adopt the euro while banks and
stock exchanges begin using euros in all scriptural transactions like
writing checks, using credit and charge cards, as well as buying
stocks and bonds;
</P>
<P>
January 2002 -- Euro bank notes and coins become legal tender;
</P>
<P>
July 2002 -- National currencies of the 11 euro countries will no
longer be accepted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
