<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Recovers Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Contractual foreign investment in
China has reversed last year's pessimistic trend to achieve a
significant 10.07-percent increase during the first quarter this
year.
</P>
<P>
"The whole year of 1998 will also see a steady development of
the direct foreign investment flowing into China," today's China
Daily quoted Zhang Shangtang, vice-chairman of the China Assn of
Enterprises with Foreign Investment, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zhang dismissed the prevailing worry that China's foreign
investment inflow will suffer a sharp reduction this year as a
result of the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"The strengthened emphasis put on foreign investment absorption
by governments at different levels will greatly propel the drive,"
said Zhang, who is also vice-chairman of the International
Investment Research Center under the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The National Conference on Foreign Investment Administration
held last year reaffirmed the priority status of foreign
investment absorption, smoothing over criticism on this issue.
</P>
<P>
High demand on the domestic market, buoyed by the large-scale
reform of the State enterprises and the large increases in
government investment in infrastructure, offers abundant
opportunities for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Aiming to achieve 8-percent growth this year, the Chinese
Government has announced a US$750-billion investment in
infrastructure projects in a bid to ginger up domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
"The improvement of the relationship across the Taiwan Straits
has also considerably pushed forward the mainland's foreign
investment inflows," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Taiwan has undergone tremendous development
during the first quarter this year, with contractual investment
capital tripling compared to the same period last year and
actually utilized capital multiplying 14 times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
