<HEADLINE> Venezuela's Foreign Currency Reserves Diminish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Foreign currency reserves in
Venezuela were 14.61 billion U.S. dollars at the end of April, a
4.3-billion-dollar drop from 18.91 billion dollars in November
last year.
</P>
<P>
The drop was attributed to a strong demand of dollars in the
market, which has forced the Central Bank of Venezuela to put into
circulation nearly 100 million dollars a day to protect the value
of its national currency bolivar.
</P>
<P>
The current electoral climate has also increased the demand of
the dollar, because major investment funds have been ordered to
leave the country until the end of the campaign when the political
situation is clear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
