<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Summit Confirms Euro XI  (Part 4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The founder countries of the euro, as the new single currency
is known, are scheduled to adopt the new currency next January
when banks and exchanges will start using euro in all scriptural
transactions such as writing checks, using credit and charge
cards, and buying bonds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
Euro bank notes and coins will become legal tender on January
1, 2002, and national currencies of the euro founder countries
will completely stop circulating by July 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which is serving the rotating presidency of the
15-nation EU, Sweden and Denmark have opted out of the euro club
whereas Greece has been judged by the commission not economically
ready to join in.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of introducing the euro is estimated to be 1 to
1.5 percent of the gross domestic product of the 11 euro founding
countries.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the euro, however, would be deemed incomplete if
the European economy and finance ministers (ECOFIN) could not
agree who should head the future ECB.
</P>
<P>
The ECOFIN council meeting is slated for later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the Netherlands are backing Dutchman Wim
Duisenberg, who is now chairman of the European Monetary
Institute, the actual forerunner of the ECB, whereas France is
championing its central banker Jean-Claude Trichet.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair Friday went to the
Netherlands on a lightning visit for talks with his Dutch
counterpart Wim Kok on the candidate of the ECB president.
</P>
<P>
EU Commission sources said that Finland failed to provide a
compromise candidate through its central bank governor Sirkka
Hamalainen.
</P>
<P>
The EU's Maastricht Treaty stipulates that the chosen candidate
serves an eight-year non-renewable term but European Commission
President Santer has confirmed that his institution could breach
the treaty by splitting the term for Trichet to succeed Duisenberg
for four years in office each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> japan to Recover in Two Years: Japanese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy may recover within
two years if the measures adopted adhered closely to the stimulus
package announced last month, the Sunday Nation quoted visiting
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi as saying Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said Japan is undergoing a major restructuring program
amidst a wide range of problems facing the country, such as
chronic economic difficulties, corruption in the administrative
system and increasing pressure to liberalize its markets and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
On April 24, the Japanese government announced its largest-ever
economic package, including more than 12 trillion yen (92.3
billion U.S. dollars) in tax cuts to stimulate demand to boost its
beleaguered economy.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also stressed the importance of interdependency among
nations, saying Japan could not progress alone.
</P>
<P>
The sluggishness of the Japanese economy has been a major
concern to many Asian nations, which are struggling to recover
from the regional financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's three-nation tour, starting from Thailand on Friday,
aimed to demonstrate Japan's commitment in the southeast Asian
region and its support for crisis-hit nations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the Japanese foreign minister pledged a
151.7- million-U.S.-dollar loan for employment and agriculture
schemes in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The "fast-disbursing" loan would be co-financed by the World
Bank and attract interest of one percent, Japanese Foreign
Ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister Saturday witnessed the signing ceremony
of an agreement to offer grant-in-aid totaling 168,200 dollars
directly to Thai welfare groups to support their grass-roots
schemes aimed at helping the poor hit by the country's economic
downturn and emergency assistance to Thai students in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi left Thailand later Saturday for Malaysia. After the
visit there, he will head for Singapore to discuss the region's
economic problems ahead of the group of eight industrial powers
summit in Birmingham, England in mid-may. 
</P>
</TEXT>
