<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Supports U.S. Middle East Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, May 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) supports the U.S. initiative for breaking the deadlock of
Middle East peace process, said PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters after holding talks with U.S. Vice
President Al Gore, Arafat said the U.S. initiative could help
bring the Middle East peace process back on track and the United
States should put more pressure on Israel and ask it to accept
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
In the new initiative, the U.S. reportedly asks Israel to hand
over 13.1 percent of the West Bank territories to the PNA during
the next stage troop redeployment. But Israel refuses to accept
it, saying it could only withdraw no more than 9 percent of the
lands in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Due to Israel's refusal, the U.S. has not announced the
initiative so far, which is also said to ask Israel to have a
"time-out" over settlement activities, both Israel and the PNA to
strengthen security cooperation and the two sides to reach an
agreement on how to move onto the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that some progress has been made in bringing
the peace process back on track, but more efforts are needed
to move it forward.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Arafat and Gore exchanged views on how to
break the impasse of the process and Arafat briefed the guest
about PNA's stands concerning the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, a PNA official close to Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed his grave concern over the deadlocked process
and asked the U.S. to officially announce its initiative and put
more pressure on Israel to implement the signed agreements, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
Gore arrived here Saturday midnight from Saudi Arabia for
talks with arafat and left for Cairo early Sunday morning. He
paid an official visit to Israel before he went to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will visit Cairo on Sunday before flying to London
to attend the London meetings at which U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will meet him and Israel Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu respectively on the mideast peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
