<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Summit Confirms Euro XI  (Part 3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The euro zone, to come into existence on January 1, 1999, is to
become a comparable economy with that of the United States and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Euro XI foundation countries generated 5.546
trillion ECU in gross domestic product, accounting for 19.4
percent of the world total, while the U.S. had 6.848 trillion ECU
or 19.6 percent and Japan 3.712 trillion ECU or 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, the Euro XI accounted for 18.6 percent of the
world trade, compared with 16.6 percent by the U.S. and 8.2
percent by Japan.
</P>
<P>
Export-wise, the Euro XI accounted for 20 percent of the world
total with a surplus of 89.7 billion ECU whereas the U.S.,
accounting for 16 percent of the world total, entailed a deficit
of 183.1 billion ECU. Japan took up 10 percent of the world export
market and had a surplus of 75.8 billion ECU.
</P>
<P>
Citibank, the world's largest foreign exchange operator, and
ABN-AMRO, a Dutch bank, have both announced plans to quote prices
for the euro for their clients starting next Monday, in a strong
sign that the financial markets have accepted the new single
currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
