<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protesters in Six U.S. States Demand Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 people marched
outside America's largest handgun maker in Massachusetts Saturday
to protest against gun-shootings that kill thousands of people
each year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The protest outside Smith &AMP; Wesson in Springfield was one of
several scheduled to be held Saturday outside the country's
largest gun makers in Connecticut, Georgia, Maryland,
Massachusetts and Virginia, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The protesters in Massachusetts laid out 5,285 pairs of shoes
to represent the number of young people age 19 and under who died
from gunshots in 1995, the latest year for which statistics were
available, the report said.
</P>
<P>
About 100 people demonstrated in Southport, Connecticut, to
protest at Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Co. Another group of some 100 people
protested in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 people died in gun-related violence between 1985
and 1995. However the U.S. Congress is now only considering a
child access prevention bill intended to educate parents about
proper gun storage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
