<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Summit Confirms Euro XI  (Part 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The one-day special summit, held under heavy guard by gendarme
and police forces, accepted and approved the convergence reports
and recommendation by the European Commission and the European
Monetary Institute, only after a much prolonged argument on the
appointment of the president of the future European Central Bank
(ECB).
</P>
<P>
The approval was not yet announced formally by either British
Prime Minister Tony Blair or EU Commission President Jacques
Santer. It was confirmed by a EU presidency official from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Both the European Commission and the European Monetary
Institute put forward their convergence reports and recommendation
on March 25 and the European Parliament approved the
recommendation Thursday with a vote of 402-79 with 27 abstentions
in favor of the recommendation.
</P>
<P>
The European legislators carried out another round of balloting
Saturday just prior to the summit by heads of state and
government. They voted 467-65 in favor with 24 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The European Council of Economy and Finance Ministers Friday
gave its unanimous approval.
</P>
<P>
The economic and monetary union in Europe, a dream cherished in
the past five decades by European statesmen, has by now become a
reality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
