<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Neill Wins Record Australian Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Susie O'Neill won a record 30th
Australian national title on the final night of competition at the
Australian Commonwealth Games swimming trials on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill, a world and Olympic champion, won the women's 200
meters butterfly for the seventh successive year to lift her total
of national titles to 30 -- one more than the long-standing mark
of Frank Beaurepaire.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old took gold in two minutes 9.62 seconds ahead of
Olympic and world championship runner-up Petria Thomas.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to O'Neill, Australia's dual Olympic champion
Kieren Perkins scraped into the team by finishing third in the
men's 1500 meters freestyle final.
</P>
<P>
Perkins finished more than 15 seconds behind reigning world
champion Grant Hackett, who recorded his second sub-15 minute swim
with a time of 14:56.23.
</P>
<P>
A number of proven performers were left out of the team,
including women's 200 meters breaststroke world record holder
Rebecca Brown and backstroker Matt Welsh, a member of the
Australian medley relay that won gold at January's world
championships in Perth .
</P>
<P>
Brown finished third in her event while Welsh was left out
despite finishing second in the 200 backstroke and fourth in the
100.
</P>
<P>
The youngest member of the squad is 14-year-old individual
medley swimmer Jennifer Reilly. Veteran breaststroker Phil Rogers,
27, is the oldest.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Games will be held in Malaysia between
September 11 and 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
