<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECB President Appointed With Much Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The official launch of the single
currency ran on Saturday into nail-biting delay, with the summit
of European heads of state and government dragging on without a
definite decision.
</P>
<P>
Finally at a press conference delayed for more than five hours,
a spokesman instead of British Prime Minister Tony Blair, chairman
of Saturday's summit, announced that the meeting had appointed Wim
Duisenberg to a full eight-year term as the head of future
European Central Bank (ECB).
</P>
<P>
But he added that the Dutch chief of the European Monetary
Institute promised to step down before his term expires though he
indicated that he would stay long enough to see through the
introduction of euro bank notes and coins being put into
circulation. That will be the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
This means that Duisenberg would not be able to complete his
eight-year mandate and retire early as a pre-arranged compromise
so as to leave vacancy for someone else.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that this succeeding man should be a French
but he added that Duisenberg is the one to decide when to step
down instead of by other politicians.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that the formation of the ECB executive
board of six was so important that it had to be done fully and
properly and it took time.
</P>
<P>
What caused the delay, however, was believed to be a
German-French row over the ECB chief candidate.
</P>
<P>
Germany and the Netherlands were backing Duisenberg whereas
France wanted its own central banker to serve as the ECB
president, a very important position, equal to that of the
chairman of the United States Federal Reserves.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Saturday's summit, according to sources close to the
commission, several compromises had been tried. One compromise
tried to arrange a half-term succession by Bank of France governor
Jean-Claude Trichet to Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
French president Jacques Chirac asked the commission to make it
an explicit guarantee when Duisenberg would make his premature
step-down to make room for Trichet.
</P>
<P>
This was described as a face-saving attempt by France to offset
the location of the ECB in Germany's Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the meeting was close to agreeing on
the other members of the ECB executive board but said no when
asked whether the meeting had set itself a deadline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
