<DOCNO> XIE19980503.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-02 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Agrees to Carry U.N. Relief Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Minister of Social
Planning El-Tayeb Ibrahim Mohamed Kheir said Saturday Khartoum
agreed to four additional U.N. aircraft of relief supplies to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has distributed 40,000 tonnes of
foodstuffs provided by the United Nations and other organizations
to the hunger-stricken areas in south Sudan, Kheir told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The government has offered all facilities possible, such as customs
exemption and approval of the movements of U.N. planes and staff,
in the life-line operation, he added.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed his government's commitment to ensuring a success
of the operation and opening all the agreed-upon routes for
delivering the relief supplies to the poor areas.
</P>
<P>
Funds for relief program needs 109 million U.S. dollars while
the donor countries have only provided 7 million dollars so far, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the international community to pressure the
rebel Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) to accept a
ceasefire for humanitarian considerations.
</P>
<P>
He accused the SPLA of planting obstacles on the road of relief
supplies and exacerbating the sufferings of the 15-year civil war
between the Sudanese government and the SPLA.
</P>
<P>
Kheir confirmed that the foodstuffs were available in the
government-controlled areas in Bahr El-Ghazal, dismissing the
allegation by the SPLA that 350,000 people were suffering from
huger in the area.
</P>
<P>
"The allegation aims to serve as a pretext for foreign
interference in the affairs of Sudan," he added.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it accused the SPLA of attacking some
government-controlled areas that opened to relief workers, adding
that most of the hunger-stricken areas were under the control of
the SPLA.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's positive response to more U.N. relief came among
accusations by some western countries that Sudan violated the
human rights and laid some 350,000 hungry people open to death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
